<HEAD>Improved Weather Helps Battle Against Wyoming Fires</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 13th graf, `In addition...' to UPDATE
with report on helicopter crash; picks up 14th graf, `Officials
in...' INSERTS 1 graf after 15th graf, `They'll be...' to UPDATE
with containment of Warm Springs fire expected Tuesday; picks up
16th graf, `Elsewhere in...' SUBS last 2 grafs, `The Hellroaring
... 12,000 acres' to UPDATE with downward revision in Hellroaring
Creek acreage, containment of Kirby fire expected Tuesday.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Temperatures fell, the wind died down and the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> arrived Monday, improving conditions for weary firefighters battling forest fires that have charred thousands of acres of <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>, especially in Yellowstone National Park. A first wave of 612 infantrymen from <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lewis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>, landed at <LOCATION> Bozeman </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mont. </LOCATION>, and headed for the 157,000-acre Clover Mist fire in <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION>'s northeastern corner. Soldiers were to help prevent the fire, one of 10 burning in the park involving about 350,000 acres, from crossing into <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Custer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> or commercial areas of <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>'s Shoshone National Forest Park spokeswoman <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> <PERSON> Anzelmo </PERSON> said it was possible some of the soldiers might remain in the southern <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> towns of <LOCATION> Cooke </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> and Silvergate to help protect them from the Clover Mist fire burning about 3 miles to the south. Approximately 3,000 firefighters were at work in <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION>, the nation's first national park. Elsewhere, reinforcements were called out in <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> to back up firefighters working to keep the 700-acre Eagle Bar fire away from a timber sale tract in the <ORGANIZATION> Payette </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION>. Spokeswoman <PERSON> Carla </PERSON> <PERSON> Tipton </PERSON> said two 20-member crews were on the scene and three more were expected; an order was put in for 280 more people. Wind blew at only 5 to 15 mph Monday in <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION>, down from Saturday's 60 mph gusts. However, the park's south entrance remained closed, forcing visitors coming from the south to detour about 150 miles to the park's west entrance at <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION>, Mont. The northern gate and two eastern entries remained open. Other roads closed included the road from the south entrance to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Thumb </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Junction </LOCATION>, on the shore of <LOCATION> Yellowstone </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION>; the road from <ORGANIZATION> Madison </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Junction </ORGANIZATION> to <PERSON> Norris </PERSON> <PERSON> Juction </PERSON> and on to Indian <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION>; and from <PERSON> Norris </PERSON> to Canyon Junction, an east-west shortcut between the western and eastern sides of the main road that circles the park in a rough hourglass pattern. The closings basically cut off the shortest route between the west and north entrances. And closing the Norris-Canyon road meant the trip from <LOCATION> Madison </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Junction </LOCATION> on the western side of the park to the famous Fishing Bridge in the east went from 39 miles up to 54, by way of the Old Faithful geyser. The majority of the park remained accessible. In addition, the <LOCATION> Grant </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Village </LOCATION> area, which contains a hotel, campground, visitor center and park staff dormitories, was closed, as were the Norris, <LOCATION> Pebble </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Madison </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> <PERSON> Lake </PERSON> campgrounds. The park contains 12 campgrounds. South of <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION>, in Grand Teton National Park and the <ORGANIZATION> Bridger-Teton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION>, the Hunter fire that had grown to more than 2,900 acres in one day had calmed Monday, said <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Bright </PERSON>, fire information officer. In addition, firefighters completed bulldozer lines around the southwest and northwest flanks of the Hunter blaze, and officials allowed residents evacuated Saturday to return to their homes, as well as guests of the <ORGANIZATION> Teton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Lost </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ranch </LOCATION>, Bright said. Meanwhile, a preliminary investigation concluded that a helicopter involved in firefighting efforts in the <ORGANIZATION> Bighorn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> crashed after it lost power to its rear rotor, which stabilizes the craft. Investigators are unsure why the rotor lost power, fire information officer <PERSON> Harvalou </PERSON> <PERSON> Buchanan </PERSON> said. Last Friday's crash killed <PERSON> Merrin </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodgers </PERSON>, 51, a <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Land </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> communications technician, and injured the pilot and two other passengers. Officials in <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION> took advantage of the calmer, cooler weather to have crews dig a fire line by hand in rugged terrain along the southern edge of the 13-day-old Warm Springs Creek fire, southeast of <PERSON> Helena </PERSON>. `` They'll be right at the burning edge,'' fire information officer <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Krepps </PERSON> said Monday. He said the 37,200-acre fire was only smoldering there Monday, allowing crews to go in with less risk. Officials predicted the fire would be contained Tuesday night. Elsewhere in <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>, 20 smokejumpers parachuted into the <LOCATION> Storm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> fire that has burned 22,000 acres of the Absaroka-Beartooth Wilderness, and 80 more were to be taken in by four-wheel drive vehicles, said Beartooth District Ranger <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaquith </PERSON>. The fire raced eight miles in a matter of hours Saturday, kicked up by high wind, he said. The Hellroaring Creek fire, in a different section of the same giant wilderness area northeast of Yellowstone National Park, had covered an estimated 24,400 acres by Monday. Spokeswoman <PERSON> Maggie </PERSON> <PERSON> Pittman </PERSON> said about 360 firefighters were working on the blaze, which officials hope will burn into natural barriers. In southeastern <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>, officials called for reinforcements to help battle a blaze out of control south of the Northern Cheyenne Indian Reservation. <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Kendall </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lands </ORGANIZATION> said the <PERSON> Kirby </PERSON> fire _ fanned by wind blowing at 35 to 40 mph _ had grown to 10,000 to 12,000 acres, but firefighters expected to contain the blaze Tuesday.
