<HEAD>Reports Up To 710 Soviets Killed In Afghan Rocket Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A British newspaper said Tuesday up to 710 Soviet soldiers and civilians were killed in a rocket attack by Afghan rebels on a military base north of <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, the capital of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> said its account of the rocket assault, that occurred either Aug. 10 or 11, was based on reports received in <LOCATION> Peshawar </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, from Afghan guerrillas. Earlier reports had surfaced from diplomatic and guerrilla sources of the attack on the <LOCATION> Kalagay </LOCATION> military base 100 miles north of <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, but they had few details and a lower death toll. <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> correspondent <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Bone </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Peshawar </LOCATION> reported a spokesman for a guerrilla group said the rockets devastated the Kalagay ammunition depot and turned the Soviet compound into an inferno. Bone quoted the spokesman, who was not identified, as saying, `` Maybe it was lucky but it was a good hit and our greatest day.'' Western diplomatic sources in <LOCATION> Islamabad </LOCATION> had said at least 109 Soviet soldiers died at <LOCATION> Kalagay </LOCATION>. Bone said the casualties were much higher according to a report written on cloth by <PERSON> Muhibullah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khan </PERSON>, a guerrilla commander in the <LOCATION> Kalagay </LOCATION> district, and received in <LOCATION> Peshawar </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bone </PERSON> said <PERSON> Muhibullah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khan </PERSON>'s report quoted a leader of the government militia as saying 598 Soviet soldiers and 112 Soviet civilians were killed and 284 Soviets were wounded. He wrote that the report said the guerrillas fired eight 107mm rockets into the supply base. Western reporters generally are barred from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and there was no independent confirmation of conflicting claims by the government and guerrillas. If the report attributed to <PERSON> Muhibullah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khan </PERSON> was accurate, it would be possibly the worst single loss by <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> forces since they entered <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> in December 1979 to help the Marxist government battle the rebels. Under an accord signed by <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> with Soviet participation last April, all Soviet military personnesl are to be withdrawn from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> by Feb. 15. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> had up to 115,000 troopers in the country but announced that half of the force had been removed as of Aug. 15 according to the withdrawal schedule. The anti-communist guerrillas did not participate in the peace negotiations and have vowed to continue their fight.
