<HEAD>Third Depression Forms In Tropical Atlantic</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 2, 4, 11 graf with 10:30 p.m. advisories, new
positions</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hurricane forecasters Monday were tracking three tropical depressions, the closest one expected to gradually strengthen as it moves into the western <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>. The newest tropical depression formed Monday in the middle <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION>, east of the <LOCATION> Lesser </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antilles </LOCATION>. The westward-moving system's highest sustained winds were near 35 mph around a center roughly 325 miles east of the island of <LOCATION> Guadeloupe </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hurricane </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in suburban <LOCATION> Coral </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gables </LOCATION> reported at 10:30 p.m. Monday. The depression was moving about 20 to 25 mph. An <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> reconnaissance aircraft was scheduled to investigate the depression Tuesday morning. Forecasters were most concerned with the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> depression, which was moving west-northwest at about at about 15 to 20 mph and had highest sustained winds of near 35 mph, the hurricane center said. The poorly organized depression was about 175 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Kingston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION>. `` The one in the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> probably has the best potential,'' said forecaster <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Case </PERSON>. `` Once it moves into the western <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>, it seems more favorable for development.'' Some strengthening was expected over the next 24 hours, <ORGANIZATION> Case </ORGANIZATION> said Monday. `` Any time there's a tropical depression southeast of us at this time of year, you need to pay attention,'' Case added. Of the tropical activity, <PERSON> Case </PERSON> said it was `` quite normal'' at this point in the hurricane season, which began June 1 and ends Nov. 30. `` We're really approaching the peak of the season,'' he said. Little strengthening was expected in the newly formed depression unless it slowed its forward speed, Case said. Meanwhile, the most distant system, located about 200 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Santo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antao </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Verde </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> off <LOCATION> west </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, was moving northwest at 15 to 20 mph into colder water, and little change in strength was expected until a gradual decrease late Tuesday. Its highest sustained winds were estimated near 35 mph. Depressions are upgraded to named tropical storms when their sustained winds reach 39 mph and to hurricanes when winds hit 74 mph. There have been two tropical storms so far in the 1988 <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> hurricane season, but neither reached hurricane strength.
