SUBS 10th graf, Thompson is ... to appear, to CORRECT to Quayle
sted Bush being invited; edits to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sen. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> told a veterans group Monday `` absolutely no influence was used'' to get him into the <ORGANIZATION> Indiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> during the height of the Vietnam War. In brief remarks to a convention of the Veterans of Foreign Wars in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, the Republican vice presidential nominee: `` Influence was not even necessary if I had chosen to use it, which I never would have. `` The reason is because my <ORGANIZATION> Indiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> unit had openings before I applied, they had openings when I applied, and they had openings after I applied. So there was absolutedly no influence used.'' The crowd of about 2,500 veterans cheered and whistled turing the hastily called appearance, in which the <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> senator joked: `` My national guard unit was never called up to active duty, but let me say that after these last 72 hours no one can say I've never faced combat.'' Presidential nominee <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and his aides have sought to play down suggestions that <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s candidacy needed shoring up after a rocky week dominated by the controversy over whether <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, a pro-military conservative on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>, pulled strings to enter the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> in 1969 as his college draft deferment was about to end. In a report in Tuesday's editions of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>, the guard official who swore in <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said he received no special treatment. Retired major general <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ahner </PERSON> said in a telephone interview that `` there had to have been a vacancy before he enlisted.'' The -LRB- <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION> -RRB- Plain Dealer reported, however, that records show the guard under a virtual freeze on recruitment imposed 49 days before <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s enlistment on May 19, 1969. The documents also appear to contradict assertions from some former <ORGANIZATION> Indiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> officers that the Guard had more than 200 vacancies and therefore was open to <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> without special treatment or favoritism, the story said. At the VFW conference, where <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had appeared earlier Monday, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> also said he hoped to put the issue of his military record behind him so attention could be focused on `` the real issues'' of the campaign. `` The question before all of us is: Not what <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> did 20 years in the past _ but what either President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> or President <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> will do in the future to secure world peace,'' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said. The circumstances surrounding <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s unplanned, last-minute appearance before the veterans group were in dispute. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON> <PERSON> LaDue </PERSON>, the spokesman for the organization, said <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> was invited Monday after Illinois Gov. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> intervened with Commander in Chief Earl Stock. <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> is a key <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> supporter in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> press secretary <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Prosperi </PERSON> said <PERSON> Stock </PERSON> made the invitation. <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON>, communications director for the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, said members of the VFW encouraged <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> to persuade <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> to appear. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> flew back to the nation's capital Sunday, accompanied by <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s campaign chairman and top strategist, to meet with the new campaign staff assembled for him by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> aides. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> departed from his prepared remarks to a Veterans of Foreign Wars convention in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> on Monday to defend his running mate: `` <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> served in the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION>, signing up in a unit that had vacancies at the time and now he is under shrill partisan attack,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said, his voice rising. `` So let his attackers cast the first stone. He served honorably. True, he did n't go to <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, but his unit was n't sent. `` But there's another truth _ he did not go to <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, he did not burn his draft card and he damned sure did n't burn the American flag,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said, drawing cheers and a standing ovation from the veterans. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> is scheduled to return to the campaign trail Wednesday, certain to face more questions about the Guard issue and how he got into law school when he did not meet admission requirements. He is to attend legislative conferences in <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>, before traveling to <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>, where aides say he will deliver a major address to the Enlisted Association of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION>, composed of current and former enlisted personnel. Meanwhile, <ORGANIZATION> Newsweek </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> magazine </ORGANIZATION> report