<SECOND>AM-Valerie's Lawsuit,0554</SECOND>
<HEAD>Valerie Harper Denies She Tried to Control `Valerie' Show</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Actress <PERSON> Valerie </PERSON> <PERSON> Harper </PERSON> denied from the witness stand Monday that she demanded absolute control over the TV series she was fired from, declaring, `` I was n't trying to be <PERSON> Genghis </PERSON> <PERSON> Khan </PERSON>.'' `` I wanted to have participation, early knowledge of stories so I would be in a partnership on the show,'' she said of her situation comedy series `` Valerie.'' Ms. <PERSON> Harper </PERSON> was called to the stand by attorneys for <ORGANIZATION> Lorimar </ORGANIZATION>, the production company suing her for alleged breach of contract. She is countersuing the company, contending it wrongfully fired her from the show. Attorney <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Engel </PERSON> sought to show that Ms. <PERSON> Harper </PERSON> was aware of all aspects of her 1985 contract with <PERSON> Lorimar </PERSON> and tried to renegotiate it because she craved more money and total control over all aspects of the show. Ms. <PERSON> Harper </PERSON> denied this, saying that she left business matters in the hands of her husband, <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Cacciotti </PERSON>, and left the contract to her agent and lawyer whose advice she later came to doubt. `` I'm not good with contracts,'' she said, holding the <ORGANIZATION> Lorimar </ORGANIZATION> document. `` I read these and start to get cross-eyed.'' Ms. <PERSON> Harper </PERSON> acknowledged that even before the pilot for `` Valerie'' was sold, her relations with other members of the production staff began to erode. The first problem, she said, arose when <PERSON> Cacciotti </PERSON>'s name was left off the list of credits on the pilot for `` Valerie'' even though he had acted as supervising producer. `` I was disappointed and hurt,'' she said. `` It felt like a betrayal.'' She told jurors that she and <PERSON> Cacciotti </PERSON> have been business partners since 1979 and have been married just over a year. <PERSON> Engel </PERSON> enumerated the financial terms of the contract that brought Ms. <PERSON> Harper </PERSON> $ 1.5 million for the first one-and-a-half seasons on the air and provided profit shares and escalating salaries for her and her husband in subsequent years. In the sixth season, she would have received $ 90,000 per episode. `` Did n't you realize that you had a very favorable deal?'' asked <PERSON> Engel </PERSON>. `` I felt financially it was a start,'' Ms. <PERSON> Harper </PERSON> replied. She faulted herself for letting too many unwritten agreements stay out of the contract. `` There was a rush to sign the contract and -LRB- they said -RRB- we'll work out the details later,'' she said Ms. <PERSON> Harper </PERSON> said, she sought to renegotiate her contract later to increase her salary and put in writing her creative participation in story ideas for each episode. By then, she conceded, she felt she was losing the right to affect story lines. `` The consultation I had enjoyed had eroded and the relationship with -LRB- the producers -RRB- had started to turn,'' she said. `` What you thought you had was total control,'' said <PERSON> Engel </PERSON>. `` I would disagree,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Harper </PERSON>. `` I wanted participation, not control ... I was n't trying to be <PERSON> Genghis </PERSON> <PERSON> Khan </PERSON>. I wanted participation with people I loved and respected.'' <PERSON> Lorimar </PERSON> fired Ms. <PERSON> Harper </PERSON> from the show a year ago and replaced her with <PERSON> Sandy </PERSON> <PERSON> Duncan </PERSON>. The show is now known as `` The <PERSON> Hogan </PERSON> Family.'' Ms. <PERSON> Harper </PERSON>'s testimony came on her 48th birthday, but the event was not mentioned in the courtroom.
