<HEAD>Major Changes Announced in Cambodian Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Heng </PERSON> <PERSON> Samrin </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> has retired or shifted 11 members of his Cabinet and abolished the office of cooperation with Soviet bloc allies, state-run radio said. The radio report, seen Sunday in <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION>, said the reshuffle included the key portfolios of defense and interior. No reason was given for the changes. The moves were made Saturday at `` an ordinary meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> in the presence of Comrade <PERSON> Heng </PERSON> <PERSON> Samrin </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION>,'' the broadcast said. <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> installed the <PERSON> Heng </PERSON> <PERSON> Samrin </PERSON> government when it invaded <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> in late 1978. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> recognizes as <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>'s legitimate government a coalition of three guerrilla groups fighting the Vietnamese occupation `` It is decided to dissolve the office of the minister of economic and cultural cooperation with <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Laos </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, and other fraternal socialist countries,'' the radio said. The Soviet-backed Vietnamese have pledged to withdraw by early 1990 the up to 100,000 troops they maintain in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>.
