<SECOND>PM-Britain-Arms Dealer, Bjt,0829</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Arms Sales Boom: From Bullets To Jet Fighters
^An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> is booming as an arms dealer, supplanting the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> as wealthy <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>'s biggest supplier and edging out long-time rival <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> globally as purveyor of everything from bullets to jet fighters. Less particular than the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> about who buys its increasingly sophisticated wares, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> has doubled its sales in the past three years through a mixture of politics, hard-sell and technical advances. The most glittering prize is a $ 17 billion deal clinched last month with <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> that includes 50 Tornado fighter-bombers. It underlines <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s major advantage over the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>: there are no political constraints on British arms sales to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s Arab enemies. `` The number of restrictions the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has on sales is preposterous,'' says <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> Tusa </PERSON>, analyst at the London-based <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION>. `` The Saudis have made it clear that they are not going to be told any longer by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, ` You can have what you want _ but only a third of it and not for another five years and providing you do n't base it where you want to','' he said in an interview. With the ink just dry on the <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> deal, <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Younger </PERSON> was back in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, this time in <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>, talking arms. About the same time, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> blocked the sale of Maverick air-to-surface missiles that were to accompany 40 American F-18 fighters <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> had agreed to buy, throwing doubt on the near $ 2 billion deal. `` Our friends and friendly rivals have their problems,'' acknowledged an official of the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exports </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, requesting anonymity. With a staff of 250, the organization's main job is to oil the wheels of sales drives by privately owned British armament manufacturers, such as the airplane giant British Aerospace, and also check that they do n't sell to banned countries. These include <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, which is officially under a <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> arms embargo since the 1982 invasion of <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. According to <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> figures, between 1985 and 1987 <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> doubled to 12 percent its share of the world arms market outside the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> says, is now the world's third largest arms supplier, ranking well behind the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> _ `` <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> probably gives away more than we sell worldwide,'' said one official _ and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, but pushing <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> down to fourth place. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> signed defense contracts worth $ 4 billion in 1985. In 1986, the figure was nearly $ 9 billion with a first major Saudi contract to buy Tornado planes, and last year contracts totaled an estimated $ 5.6 billion. <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Export </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> chief Sir <PERSON> Colin </PERSON> <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON>, who received a knighthood this year on Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>'s recommendation, says <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s 1987 figure keeps it ahead of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. In 1986, with the <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> deal, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> moved temporarily into second place, ahead of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. Mrs. <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> has assiduously cultivated the oil-rich Saudis on official visits and rolled out the red carpet for King Fahd in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. She slips in plugs for British armaments during foreign trips, including recently in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, where <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> are competing for a multimillion-dollar order for nuclear-powered submarines. British officials, arms manufacturers and some analysts say prime factors in the increased sales are improved weapons and warplanes, including the multinational Tornado developed with <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, and the free-enterprise atmosphere generated by nearly a decade of <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> government. `` It is a fact that we're producing more things with fewer people,'' said a British official, adding the 130,000-strong workforce in the defense industry has declined slightly in the past few years. He requested anonymity. Others familiar with the secretive world of arms sales say <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> has also been hurt by a tradition of gearing arms exports to Third World countries on generous credit terms. <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>, marketing director for <ORGANIZATION> Plessey </ORGANIZATION>, one of five British defense electronics manufacturers, said that with <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> cutting defense spending, companies are forced to expand foreign sales. `` We have to go and slug it out in the market place in the major countries,'' said <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> in an interview. <ORGANIZATION> Plessey </ORGANIZATION> says its annual turnover from defense sales has more than trebled to $ 850 million since 1980, with sonar systems going to the Swedish, <LOCATION> Thai </LOCATION> and South Korean navies, an $ 850 million communications network for the Australian army, and smaller deals with <LOCATION> Oman </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> and an unidentified Far Eastern country. But British manufacturers have suffered some big failures too. The most expensive was the scrapping of the Nimrod spy plane in 1986, after nine years' work by <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION> costing nearly $ 1.7 billion. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> ordered the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airborne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Warning </ORGANIZATION> and Command System instead.
