<BYLINE>Charles Donald Christian</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Dr. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Christian </PERSON>, who created the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arizona </ORGANIZATION> medical school's <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Obstetrics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gynecology </ORGANIZATION> in 1969 and later discovered the hazards of intrauterine devices, died of cancer Sunday at his <LOCATION> Tucson </LOCATION> home. He was 57. <PERSON> Christian </PERSON> was credited in 1974 with informing the manufacturers of the Dalkon Shield that the birth-control device was causing severe complications and death in women who used it. Data provided by <PERSON> Christian </PERSON> led the manufacturer, <ORGANIZATION> A.H. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Robins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, to issue a safety warning for the product. A year later, <ORGANIZATION> Robins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> suspended distribution of the device at the request of the <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>.
