<BYLINE>By RAFAEL CANDANEDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military personnel are reporting increased harassment by local officials, but there is no indication the actions are part of a new campaign by the government of Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> authorities said Sunday. <PERSON> Cynthia </PERSON> <PERSON> Farrell </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION>, said the incidents involved harassment, `` not attacks.'' <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> is commander of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION> and controls the civilian government. He was indicted in February by two grand juries in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> on drug trafficking charges and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has imposed economic sanctions in an effort to force him to resign and leave <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. A statement by the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION> late Sunday called the accusations of harassment part of a campaign of disinformation in an effort to destabilize <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> and listed numerous allegations of misconduct by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. Ms. <PERSON> Farrell </PERSON> said the reports of harassment are coming only from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military personnel. `` Civilians, business people and embassy personnel have reported no increase in harassment,'' she said. She added she did not know if <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military personnel are being bothered more or are `` simply reporting more cases.'' An official at the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said 240 cases of harassment had been repor