<HEAD>Bush's Running Mate Has Rocky Debut In Political Big Leagues</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RETRANSMITTING a0426 to add editor's note at end</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s rocky entry into big-league politics, stumbling over questions about his military record that threaten to overshadow <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s campaign, has left the exuberant young senator bloody but seemingly unbowed. Back in the nation's capital to prepare for his first solo campaign trip Wednesday, the <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> senator remains adamant that he is not an embarrassment to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, has not considered removing himself from the ticket, and sees nothing improper in the way he entered the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> at a time when other young men were marching off to fight in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>. But the Republican ticket's public debut at the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> convention and on a three-day Midwestern campaign swing saw these extraordinary events: _ <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, asked at a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> news conference about his reasons for going into the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> in 1969, stumbling over his thoughts and finally declaring: `` I did not know in 1969 that I would be in this room today, I confess. _ <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> standing in mock attention before a <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> farewell convention breakfast, reciting to the uneasy audience his name, rank and serial number and proclaiming `` <ORGANIZATION> Indiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> Six years and proud of it!'' _ <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, surrounded by reporters and a raucously partisan crowd in his hometown of <LOCATION> Huntington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ind. </LOCATION>, asserting `` I got into the National Guard fairly'' but acknowledging that he assumed a friend of his wealthy publishing family made calls on his behalf after <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> expressed interest in joining the Guard _ <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, telling reporters in <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> that he could not recall what communications he had with his draft board 20 years ago but insisting he distinctly remembered having no conversation `` in the 1980s'' with a <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> Democrat quoted as saying <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> told him he `` rode out'' <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> in the Guard _ <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, calling the controversy a `` tempest in a teapot'' and asserting that his initial campaign swing `` has gone great'' except for `` this frenzy'' of media interest in <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s military record Whether that assessment is accurate remains to be seen. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> seems likely to continue to have to fight portrayals of himself as a wealthy young man who spoke in favor of the Vietnam War but had strings pulled to avoid the draft as his college student deferment was about to expire. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> bomber pilot who saw extensive combat in World War II, defended his running mate, saying that the Vietnam War years in which <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, now 41, pondered his own military service `` were different times.'' As for <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> being vulnerable in the area of defense, an area in which <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has portrayed <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> as weak, the vice president said, `` The difference between the person I'm running against and my running mate are night and day on defense.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> aides insist they are happy with how <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> has handled himself in publicly answering questions about his military record. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> himself says he does not feel the issue has overshadowed <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. But there was a clear change in campaign strategy after <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s outdoor news conference Friday that was piped over a public address system to <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s hometown supporters Their booing of reporters' questions and cheering of <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s answers helped create a circus-like atmosphere reminiscent of a Roman gladiatorial bout while <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> remained out of sight in a holding room That day, on which the ticket opened its first joint campaign trip in the nation's heartland, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> dominated news stories about the event. The next day, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> took charge, defending his running mate in no uncertain terms at a joint news conference and declaring that <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s qualifications and background had been examined to his satisfaction. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said his aides had to spend a lot of time last week running down `` rumor after insidious rumor,'' and added that the controversy `` is behind us.'' However, some questions may yet need to be answered. There have been conflicting reports, for example, on whether there were vacancies in the Guard at the time <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> entered or whether there was a waiting list. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> has said he can not recall those kinds of details. And he has not spelled out publicly the extent of his knowledge about what calls were made on his behalf or to whom they were made. A retired Guard official, who is a friend of <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s family and worked for the family newspaper, has said he did contact the Guard on <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s behalf. The commander of the Guard unit to which <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> was assigned, however, has said he did not receive a call from anyone urging <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s enlistment. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> insists that `` no rules were broken'' in the way he entered the Guard. He says he was willing to serve in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> had his unit been called up, although he concedes that he was generally aware the likelihood of that happening was not great. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> has been angered at implications that he was trying to avoid the draft, although he has tried to appear unperturbed throughout the controversy. Over the weekend, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> appeared not to hear some spectators' chants of `` Quayle, who went in your place?'' or to see signs reading `` This Quayle is a chicken.'' He seems to be philosophical about the most intense and public scrutiny of his meteoric political career. `` I'm in politics in what they call the big leagues,'' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> says, adding: `` Running for the vice presidency is a definite honor.''
</TEXT>
