<FIRST>r w PM-Candidates-ForeignPolicy Bjt   08-22 0732</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Candidates-Foreign Policy, Bjt,720</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON WIRE: Do Voters Care?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>An AP News Analysis</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Foreign policy is getting very little attention from the candidates as the campaign gets started. The Republicans seem to be content to play vaguely on <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s experience, while the Democrats are saying even less Even so, the basic approach of the two parties is becoming clear. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and his running mate, Sen. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, intend to sound the traditional conservative themes of a powerful military structure and keeping a wary eye on the Russians. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and his running mate, Sen. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, are playing down ideology and playing up `` competence,'' being careful to strike a skeptical stance on the Soviets while sounding the peace theme. Both sides are bound to get more specific in the 2 -LCB- months of campaigning ahead. It's likely to get sticky. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will be challenged about the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration's secret arms sale to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> while <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' lack of foreign policy experience will be tested over a wide range of issues. Do n't look for foreign policy treatises, though. Campaigning for president in the television age encourages snappy or catchy one-liners, not a thoughtful exposition of how the candidates stand on tricky arms control issues, the <LOCATION> Arab-Israel </LOCATION> dispute, leftist movements in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and apartheid in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. Besides, politicians and their managers operate on the theory the voters are far more concerned with pocketbook issues such as jobs and inflation than with American foreign policy. There have been striking exceptions and mixed results. <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON> ran for a fourth term as president in 1944 while the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was still at war. The overriding issue was whether to take a chance on changing leaders. The voters stuck with <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON>. In 1972, on the other hand, <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> McGovern </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> candidate, ran primarily as an anti-war candidate whose opposition to <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> involvement in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> was the central theme of his futile race against President <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>. The 1988 campaign is just now unfolding, but there is no reason to believe either the Republicans or Democrats will give that sort of weight to a single foreign policy issue. In fact, the selections of <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> suggest the presidential candidates intend to place the focus elsewhere. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s choice of <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> is above all a gesture to the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION>'s most conservative elements, while <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> chose <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> primarily for his experience in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and his ties to conservative Democrats, especially in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. In 1960, when <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> was pondering a running mate for his first race for the presidency, he assembled 36 party elders at a midnight meeting in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. The governor of <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Stratton </PERSON>, offered this advice: `` You can say all you want about foreign affairs, but what is really important is the price of hogs in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> picked <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Cabot </PERSON> <PERSON> Lodge </PERSON>, who had served as the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> permanent representative at the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>. They lost to <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lyndon </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, but <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>'s explanation, as recalled by former Undersecretary of State <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON>, may still be relevant: `` If you ever let the Democrats campaign only on domestic issues, they will beat us. Our only hope is to keep it on foreign policy.'' That does n't mean, however, that the candidate has to be an expert on the pecking order in the Kremlin, the history of the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> or the strengths and weaknesses of the Nicaraguan economy. <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> won in 1980 without any experience in foreign affairs. He lacked the background to be specific about foreign policy issues. But he had a well-developed image of opposing communism, and he relied on generalities whenever dealing with the Soviets _ the primary foreign policy issue of our time _ came to the fore. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> is leaving office on an entirely different note. He has held four summit meetings with Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and signed a treaty with <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> to scrap intermediate-range nuclear missiles. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, his vice president, is trying to capitalize on the improvement in U.S.-Soviet relations, suggesting he is far more capable than <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> to maintain the momentum. The fact that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> _ like <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> _ was inexperienced when he ran for the presidency is not stopping <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> from questioning the credentials of his opponent.
</TEXT>
