<HEAD>Dukakis Emphasizes National Themes During Regional Trip</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is emphasizing national campaign themes as he visits northeastern <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, a region the Democratic presidential nominee often cites when discussing his record of economic development. As he did during a visit to central <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> last week, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is kicking off the visit with a meeting attended by area elected officials, educators and business and labor leaders. The <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor also planned today to distribute grants for a new manufacturing research center and for improvements at the <ORGANIZATION> Middlesex </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> campus in <LOCATION> Lowell </LOCATION>. From there, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> was to attend an event to promote his Homeownership Opportunity Program, which provides state assistance to low - and moderate-income families looking to buy homes <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> was to return to the northeastern corner of the state Tuesday for several more events. He frequently mentions the northeastern <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> communities of <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lowell </PERSON>, both former mill cities, when discussing his efforts to spur economic development in economically depressed areas. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> spent Sunday at his <LOCATION> Brookline </LOCATION> home, where he returned late Saturday night after a four-day campaign swing through parts of <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>. That trip started in the middle of the Republican National Convention and was part of a campaign effort to keep <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> visible during the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> gathering. Aides billed the trip as highly successful. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> revealed no new positions on issues but was widely covered in the national news media, particularly after <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> nominee <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s selection of Sen. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> as a running mate sparked controversy Questions have centered on <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s use of his wealthy family's influence to help him join the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> and avoid the draft at the height of the Vietnam War <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> at virtually every stop indirectly criticized <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s judgment for choosing him. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> repeatedly discussed the lenthy <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> record of his own running mate, Sen. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, telling crowds the `` true test'' of presidential leadership should be the quality of people selected to fill key positions. After spending today and Tuesday in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> plans to campaign Wednesday and Thursday in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>. He is scheduled to be back in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> on Friday and then back in the nation's capital Saturday to participate in a march marking the 25th anniversary of the civil rights march on <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> led by <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr </PERSON>.
