<HEAD>Soviet Rocket Descent Puts on Light Show</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Soviet rocket that plummeted to <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> in northeastern <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> put on a spectacular light show for residents of the western and northern <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, but it was not all that unusual in other respects, <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> officials say. The craft that crashed Sunday, causing no reported injuries or damage, was also not Cosmos 1900, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> spy satellite that has been drifting out of orbit for several months and arousing concern because it is nuclear-powered. The rocket had been launched last Thursday to boost a <ORGANIZATION> Gorizont </ORGANIZATION> communications satellite into orbit, said Maj. <PERSON> Alex </PERSON> <PERSON> Mondragon </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aerospace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Space Command, speaking from <ORGANIZATION> Peterson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> near <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION>. The vehicle, which came down at about 1 a.m. EDT, was most likely an SL12, one of the most frequently used Soviet launchers, he said. The craft was tracked by officials at the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Surveillance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Cheyenne </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountain </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>, where about 7,200 space vehicles are constantly being observed. An average of one space vehicle reenters the Earth's atmosphere each day, <PERSON> Mondragon </PERSON> said. `` It's not unusual for a rocket body not to stay in orbit,'' he said. `` There's nothing to keep it there.'' Cosmos 1900, launched last Dec. 12, is now expected to reenter the Earth's atmosphere in late September or early October, <PERSON> Mondragon </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Mondragon </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> spokesman Maj. <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON> provided no further details about the craft's condition when it reached the <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> or the precise location where it came down. <PERSON> Mondragon </PERSON> said it usually takes about 24 hours to pinpoint where downed satellites plummet to <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>. The spokesmen said the descending rocket was visible to residents of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>. `` I do understand it was pretty spectacular,'' <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON> said. He said the downing of the craft, which he referred to as a `` non-nuclear Soviet rocket body,'' was expected by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials. `` It was predicted it would come down, it came down as predicted and it came down where it was predicted,'' he said. <PERSON> Mondragon </PERSON> said officials do not try to recover parts of such rocket bodies because 95 percent of them usually burn up upon reentry. `` That spectacular light show that they provide folks with is the rocket body burning up,'' he said.
