<HEAD>Administration Changes Tune on Farm Loan Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s business-and-industrial loan program has become a kingpin of the administration's rural development effort, helping finance projects from catfish plants to macadamia nuts Once despised by White House budget trimmers as something local communities and private citizens ought to do for themselves, the `` B & amp; I'' loans handled by the department's <ORGANIZATION> Farmers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> have enjoyed new status in recent years. The financial battering of farmers in the early 1980s, the hardships that hit the economy of small-town <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, and the insistent demands of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> have helped jog the administration into a new look at rural development. For the fiscal year that began last Oct. 1, according to <ORGANIZATION> FmHA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Marlyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Aycock </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> B </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; I loan guarantees are expected to use the full $ 95.7 million authorized by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, the second year in a row that has happened. According to FmHA records, the <ORGANIZATION> B </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; I volume soared to more than $ 1 billion in 1979-80 before winding down under the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, which unsuccessfully for several years advocated elimination of the program. The <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>'s budget office in presenting proposals for fiscal 1984, for example, explained the reasons for seeking reduction or elimination of many of the FmHA community programs, including sewer and water assistance, and B & amp; I. `` Reductions in rural development program loans and grants reflect the administration's philosophy that private sector investment, not public sector pump priming, should drive development,'' the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> said. `` The federal role in the rural sector will be limited to that of lender of last resort in providing water, sewer and community facilities essential to the health and safety of households where most needed in rural areas.'' <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> reduced annual authorizations for B & amp; I in the early 1980s, and the administration kept the actual loan level far below that. In 1984, for example, when B & amp; I was authorized at $ 200 million, the actual lending level was held to $ 124 million. Lending dropped to $ 61 million in 1985 and to $ 55 million in 1986. Then in 1987, when <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> set the authority for <ORGANIZATION> B </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; I at $ 95.7 million, the full amount was used for the first time during the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. <PERSON> Aycock </PERSON> said that as of this April the B & amp; I program had 2,238 loans outstanding for a total of $ 1.82 billion. Of those, 475 loans, or 21 percent, were delinquent, a total of $ 230 million. In its 16 years, the <ORGANIZATION> B </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; I program has provided more than 7,000 guaranteed loans totaling nearly $ 6 billion, according to the background information provided by <ORGANIZATION> FmHA </ORGANIZATION> at the request of The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. B & amp; I was authorized by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in 1972 to provide loans `` for the purpose of improving, developing or financing business, industry and employment and improving the economic and environmental climate in rural communities, including pollution abatement and control.'' An example of the program's intent was a 1974 loan to <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cotton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Growers </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Lubbock </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, for $ 28.2 million to finance a new denim manufacturing plant in <LOCATION> Littlefield </LOCATION>, near the fields where cotton grew. Two more loans brought the total to $ 33.5 million. `` Jobs were created for more than 600 people, and a ready market was provided for Plains cotton,'' the agency said. `` It was made into high-quality denim, much of which was bought by <PERSON> Levi </PERSON> <PERSON> Strauss </PERSON> over the years. The loan was paid in full on Aug. 4, 1987.'' Some more recent examples include: _ $ 2 million for <ORGANIZATION> Fishco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Belzoni </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, to help build a catfish processing plant with a capacity of 40 million pound per year. The plant is expected to employ 432 people when running at full capacity. _ $ 2 million for <ORGANIZATION> Stoneville </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Furniture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Stoneville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, to buy equipment and machinery. Funds also will be used for working capital. The plant employs approximately 700. _ $ 4.5 million for <ORGANIZATION> Fairmont </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foods </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Fairmont </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>, to buy and reopen a food processing plant, and to purchase new machinery and equipment to produce frozen processed foods. The project will create 234 jobs. The B & amp; I loan program over the years also has been used for cotton gins, the manufacture of radar `` guns'' used by police, a shrimp farm in <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, a chicken processing, a radio station, automobile dealerships, and plants to make fuel-grade ethanol. As another recent <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> report described program operations, ventures `` range from the processing and marketing of coffee beans and macadamia nuts in <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> to the manufacturing of equipment to convert solid waste to boiler fuel in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>.'' Under the recently enacted $ 3.9 billion drought-aid package, the <ORGANIZATION> FmHA </ORGANIZATION> was ordered to use B & amp; I `` to the maximum extent possible'' to help businesses adversely affected by drought. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> included $ 200 million for guaranteed loans to rural businesses and organizations to recover from drought losses. Those loans will have a lid of $ 500,000 per individual.
