<HEAD>New Pub Hours For England and Wales</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By AUDREY WOODS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Pubs and bars throughout <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wales </LOCATION> will be allowed to stay open through the afternoon starting today, ending a 73-year-old policy and arousing some fears of increased drunkenness and violence. Pubs, clubs and hotel bars may now stay open on weekdays from 11 a.m. to 11 p.m. instead of closing between 3 p.m. and 5:30 p.m. Sunday afternoon hours have been extended by one hour, from noon until 3 p.m. In 1915 the government decreed the afternoon closing to curb drinking by munitions workers. Parliament voted overwhelmingly in April to do away with the old rules. But pubs do not have to change their hours if they do not want to, and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Licensed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Victuallers </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> predicted that almost half the 67,000 pubs in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wales </LOCATION> would stick to the old ways. Most back-street and country pubs will probably continue to call `` time'' on weekdays at 3 p.m. The <ORGANIZATION> Brewers </ORGANIZATION>' Society predicted at least 25,000 new jobs would be generated by the longer drinking hours and that pubs would win back lost trade from hamburger and pizza bars. Pub owners and brewers agree that pubs in seaside and tourist towns and city bars will benefit most from increased trade. Home Secretary <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Hurd </PERSON> said: `` I believe that the new licensing hours will benefit society as a whole by giving people greater freedom of choice. Most people drink sensibly and responsibly and it makes no sense to deny them the opportunity to enjoy a drink in the afternoon at the time they wish.'' The government has faced stiff opposition from the health lobby and critics who fear that drink-related crime, particularly drunken violence by young rowdies and drunk driving, will increase. But champions of the new hours point out that extended hours in <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>, introduced over a decade ago, were followed by a reduced incidence of drunkenness and violence. The Scottish Office said licensing changes had little impact on alcohol abuse. In <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> most pubs increased alcohol sales during the past year, in which pubs were allowed to open on Sundays for the first time and open until later on weekdays. But pub owners say there has been no increase in hooliganism and drunkenness. <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> has had all-day opening from Monday to Saturday since 1922. The possible impact on the home has not been overlooked by the press. The Sunday Mirror ran a tongue-in-cheek story this week predicting that the extra drinking hour on Sunday threatened `` to shake the fabric of British family life.'' Wives preparing Sunday dinner can no longer `` even pretend to believe the man who tells you that he's just popping out to post a letter @ take the dog for a walk.''
</TEXT>
