<HEAD>Government Bans Anti-Conscription Organization</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government today banned a nationwide organization opposed to conscription laws requiring white men to serve in the armed forces. Law and Order Minister <PERSON> Adriaan </PERSON> <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON>, acting under state-of-emergency regulations, said the End Conscription Campaign was banned from carrying out any activities. Action against the organization was expected since 143 young white men, in the broadest challenge ever of the conscription system, announced Aug. 3 that they would refuse to perform mandatory military service. Most of the men face six-year jail terms. Leaders of the End Conscription Campaign denied involvement in organizing the mass resistance, but Defense Minister <PERSON> Magnus </PERSON> <PERSON> Malan </PERSON> said he held the group responsible for the `` subversive action.'' The organization appealed unsuccessfully for a system of alternative, non-military service for men politically or morally opposed to joining the army. It has argued that no one should be forced to serve involuntarily in the army units that patrol black townships or in the forces combating pro-independence guerrillas in <LOCATION> South-West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, also known as <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON>, in a statement, said the End Conscription Campaign's primary purpose was to undermine public support for the armed forces `` The <ORGANIZATION> ECC </ORGANIZATION> attempts to create an impression of political neutrality,'' <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON> said. `` But it is not difficult to see the organization's role in the revolutionary onslaught against <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>.'' The End Conscription Campaign was formed in 1983, and many of its members were detained or restricted since a national state of emergency was declared in June 1986. In February, the organization said it suspected army involvement in a harassment campaign that included anonymous telephone calls, smear pamphlets and vandalism of members' property. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s conscription laws allow conscientious objection only for religious reasons, not on political or moral grounds. Only whites are subject to conscription _ military service for other races is voluntary. <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON> said the End Conscription Campaign's effort had been endorsed by the <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, the outlawed guerrilla group waging a sabotage and bombing campaign aimed at ending apartheid and overthrowing the South African government. <PERSON> Vlok </PERSON> also said the End Conscription Campaign had assisted draft dodgers, helping them obtain residence permits to live in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. The government no longer disclosed how many men refuse to serve in the military. In 1985, the last year figures were disclosed, 7,589 men declined to serve. The ban on the End Conscription Campaign is similar to bans imposed in February on 17 anti-apartheid organizations. Under the bans, the organizations are allowed to exist in name only. By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
