<HEAD>Muck Restored In New Edition Of Sinclair's `Jungle'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A new edition of <PERSON> Upton </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinclair </PERSON>'s `` The Jungle,'' an expose of squalid conditions in the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> stockyards, will restore whole chapters cut to make the book more marketable, a book historian says. <PERSON> Sinclair </PERSON> cut his original manuscript by a third for the 1906 Doubleday, Page edition which caused meat sales to slump and spurred President <PERSON> Theodore </PERSON> <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON> to order an investigation that led to the nation's first Pure Food and Drug Act. <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> DeGruson </PERSON>, a professor and curator of rare books at <LOCATION> Pittsburg </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> Kan. </LOCATION> -RRB- <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, was quoted in today's <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> as saying that, considering the material that was expunged from the original, `` it's amazing that the published book had any impact whatsoever.'' `` Despite his protestations that he wished the novel published as he had written it, revision was drastic,'' <PERSON> DeGruson </PERSON> wrote in the introduction to the new edition, due in October from <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Luke </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>, Tenn Most of the deletions pertained to socialism, but paragraphs criticizing the press and derogatory comments about `` big business,'' self-made men, captains of industry and marriage also were deleted. <PERSON> DeGruson </PERSON> said he pieced together the original novel from a truckload of rotting paper given to him in 1980 by a young man who had been hired to clean out the cellar of a nearby farm. The original novel had been serialized in a weekly newspaper, The Appeal, but the special edition that contained the final eight chapters and the conclusion had been lost until DeGruson found it among the papers from the farm. <PERSON> Sinclair </PERSON> died in a <LOCATION> Bound </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Brook </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, nursing home in 1968 at the age of 90 _ one year after he returned to the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> to watch President <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> sign the Wholesome Meat Act, an expansion of the bill his book inspired.
