<HEAD>Andean Condor Dies En Route to Experiment for California Condor
Recovery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL FLEEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 One zoo-hatched Andean condor died in transit to a wilderness area but three others survived for an experiment intended to show the best way to reintroduce endangered <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> condors into the wild. The surviving birds were safely placed in secret holding pens Saturday in <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Padres </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION>, and more Andean condors will be taken to the area in October, said <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Dowhan </PERSON>, condor recovery coordinator for the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Fish and <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. The dead bird was sent to <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> for an autopsy, <PERSON> Dowhan </PERSON> said. He said its death will have little effect on the program. `` In some ways, you kind of want things to go wrong now instead of later,'' he said. The South American birds, all females to prevent breeding in the wild, are being used to test techniques biologists hope to use to begin returning the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> condor to the wild after their numbers are increased in a captive breeding program. Only 28 <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> condors are known to survive, all in captivity at the <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diego </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wild </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Animal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> Zoo. The Andean condor was chosen for the experiment because it is the closest living relative to the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> condor. Though the Andean condors are also endangered, they number in the thousands. Scientists are conducting the experiment to see how birds hatched in captivity adapt to freedom and fend for themselves without native birds of their species to serve as examples. The 3 - and 4-month-old birds will spend several weeks in mesh enclosures in the forest 75 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> When the Andean birds are able to fly, around November, scientist will fit them with radio transmitters, release them and monitor their progress. The Andean birds will remain in the wild until it's time to release <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> condors, perhaps as early as 1992 if the captive breeding program continues to succeed, <PERSON> Dowhan </PERSON> said.
