<HEAD>Silver Decision Another Slip In Hunts' Fortunes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal jury's order that the Hunt brothers pay more than $ 130 million to a Peruvian company for their scheme to corner the world silver market marks another setback in the fortunes of the flamoyant <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> family. However, Saturday's jury decision in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> will have little effect on the Hunts' efforts to settle a $ 1.5 billion dispute with their lenders, a Hunt bankruptcy attorney said. Besides the legal judgment, the collapse of silver, sugar and real estate investments have all contributed to the steady decline of the family fortune, once estimated at $ 20 billion. The jury said the three <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON> brothers conspired to artificially raise the price of silver in the late 1970s to the detriment of <ORGANIZATION> Minpeco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> S.A. </ORGANIZATION>, the mining marketing company of the Peruvian government. <PERSON> Bunker </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON>, 62, and <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON>, 59, also were found to have engaged in a pattern of racketeering activity to monopolize the silver market. The case is a civil action, so no criminal penalties are attached to the finding. <PERSON> Minpeco </PERSON> had said <PERSON> Lamar </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON>, 56, owner of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Football </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Kansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chiefs </ORGANIZATION>, and his two brothers conspired unsuccessfully with several <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> businessmen to corner the silver market. But an attorney in the two-year dispute with lenders said the damages awarded in the silver battle were relatively small. `` I feel like the Hunts won,'' <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, the bankruptcy attorney representing <ORGANIZATION> Placid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which is owned by the trust estate of the Hunt brothers, told the <ORGANIZATION> Dallas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION>. The $ 130 million damages could be reduced by the $ 33.4 million amount Minpeco earned on silver it held during the period, <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> said. And $ 64.7 million, which Minpeco received from other defendants in a pretrial settlement, could also be deducted from the amount the Hunts must pay, he said. The Hunts will file motions that raise other issues in the silver case, said <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Whitaker </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Hunt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> vice president. `` The brothers are confident that this wrong result will eventually be overturned as they proceed through the court system,'' <PERSON> Whitaker </PERSON> said Saturday. At first, the Hunts, sons of the late <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> oilman H.L. Hunt, took their losses with aplomb. In March 1980, when the silver market crashed, <PERSON> Bunker </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON> said, `` A billion dollars just ai n't what it used to be. In 1986, the brothers were all on the Fortune 400 list of the richest Americans with combined estimated assets of $ 1 billion. Last year, they dropped off the list. This year, when forced to sell his seven <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> farms and 600-horse stable of thoroughbred race horses, the eldest <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON> did n't attend the auction. `` It would be too sad to watch,'' he said. The Hunts sued their banks and lenders in July 1986, after they could not renegotiate loans for their <ORGANIZATION> Placid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Penrod </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drilling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. The two companies had failed to make payments on a total of $ 1.5 billion in loans. To settle the dispute, the Hunts proposed this spring to pay $ 663.5 million from funds raised through Placid operations, primarily in the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>. Hearings on the bankruptcy settlement proposal were scheduled to begin this month.
