<HEAD>Reunion For Former Residents Of Town Lost To Reservoir</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DANA, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Dana </PERSON> has n't existed for a half-century, except in the hearts of its former residents. But for five hours Sunday, there was a homecoming for the survivors and children of the 500 people who once lived in the town, first settled in 1763 but erased 50 years ago so <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> could have drinking water. Four little central <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> towns died on April 27, 1938, on order of the state <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> to form the 38-square-mile Quabbin Reservoir, after the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> rejected their appeals. Three _ <LOCATION> Enfield </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Prescott </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Greenwich </LOCATION> _ now lie under 413 billion gallons of water. Only the <PERSON> Dana </PERSON> <PERSON> Common </PERSON>, surrounded by empty cellars on high ground on the east side of the <LOCATION> Swift </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> <LOCATION> valley </LOCATION>, escaped the inundation. `` It's the one place left where people can touch what was formerly there. Everything else is under water,'' said <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON>, who runs weekly teas for former residents, many now in the 70s and 80s. Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> declared 1988 a Year of Remembrance for the 2,500 people who lost their homes to the reservoir. Many of those who moved away have returned this spring and summer to attend events sponsored by local historical societies. `` I was just 10 years old when we had to go. It was hard,'' said <PERSON> Florence </PERSON> <PERSON> Avery </PERSON>. `` I remember them digging up the bodies in the cemetery. And my grandfather's house.'' Mrs. <PERSON> Avery </PERSON>, her five brothers and one of her five sisters, as well as her 90-year-old mother, <PERSON> Jennie </PERSON> <PERSON> Belle </PERSON> <PERSON> Coo