<HEAD>Government Backs Off On Mandatory Eviction Proposal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government on Monday withdrew a widely criticized bill that would force the evictions of tens of thousands of blacks living in areas designated for whites. Critics said the bill, which would require magistrates to evict anyone living in a neighborhood reserved by law for another race, would provoke international outrage. <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Heunis </PERSON>, minister of constitutional development and planning, said the measure would be re-introduced in parliament with amendments specifying that evictions not be mandatory. The amended bill, however, would retain other provisions strengthening enforcement of residential segregation. Leaders of the parliament's Asian and mixed-race chambers, which can not block most government-backed bills, said their houses would adjourn indefinitely to protest the new legislation. <PERSON> Heunis </PERSON> said the amended bill would allow government officials to consider the availability of alternative housing and other `` humanitarian considerations'' before approving evictions. In other ways, he said, it would remain identical to the original measure. Among the controversial measures remaining in the bill are those making it easier for authorities to confiscate property and to evict and prosecute people violating the Group Areas Act. The 35-year-old act designates racially segregated neighborhoods. Under both the new and old versions of the bill, the maximum fine for property owners who allow a person to live outside his racial area would increase from about $ 165 to $ 4,100. The maximum prison sentence would increase from two years to five years. The act is a major issue in the campaign for nationwide municipal elections Oct. 26. The government's proposal to strengthen enforcement of the act has been seen as an accommodation to right-wing whites. The government has not strictly enforced the Group Areas Act in recent years, angering conservative whites opposed to integrated neighborhoods. President P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> said last week he believes residential segregation is favored by 80 percent of whites, 70 percent of Asians and people of mixed race, and a majority of blacks. <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Hendrickse </PERSON>, leader of the mixed-race chamber of parliament, challenged <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>'s claim, saying his constituents favored total repeal of the act. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s black majority is excluded from parliament, but both the mixed-race and <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> chambers are expected to reject the Group Areas legislation and its amendments. This would force the government to refer the bill to the President's Council, a body controlled by <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. The party has the power to implement legislation over the opposition of the two non-white chambers. Parliament, which reconvened Monday after a midyear recess, also is to debate legislation on creating the first `` open areas,'' or legal multiracial neighborhoods. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> would have veto power over any such plans.
</TEXT>
