<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A terrorist campaign in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> carried out by agents of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s Soviet-backed government accounted for well over half of all incidents of state-sponsored terrorism worldwide last year, according to a <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> report released Monday. Out of 189 such cases, <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> carried out 127 against <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> in its campaign of retaliation for <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>'s backing of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s anti-communist guerrilla movement, the report said. The report was prepared before last Wednesday's incident in which a mysterious plane crash killed Pakistani President <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> <PERSON> ul-Haq </PERSON>, <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ambassador <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON> <PERSON> Raphel </PERSON>, Brig. Gen. <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Wassom </PERSON> and 27 others. Pakistani officials suspect sabotage but investigators lack conclusive evidence as to the cause of the crash, which occurred 330 miles south of <LOCATION> Islamabad </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officials, insisting on anonymity, said any comment on the cause of the crash would be speculative but added that Afghan agents have to be `` among the suspects'' because of their alleged role in fomenting terrorism in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. Diplomats at the Afghan Embassy here were unavailable for comment. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Kriesburg </PERSON>, a senior associate at the <ORGANIZATION> Carnegie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Endowment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peace </ORGANIZATION>, said it would be a mistake to assume automatically that Afghan agents were responsible for the crash because <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> had many other enemies. They included some from within the Pakistani military and others who were alienated by his authoritarian rule. The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> compilation indicated that Afghan-sponsored terrorist acts almost tripled those of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, listed second with 44. <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> was third with 7 terrorist episodes. All told, there were 832 international terrorist incidents last year, according to the study. `` When the Pakistani numbers are subtracted, the number of incidents in the rest of the world declined by almost 10 per cent from 1986 statistics,'' the report said. It said the <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> campaign is being waged by the <ORGANIZATION> Afghan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION>, known by the acronym WAD. <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> said last November that the assassinations and bombings carried out against Pakistani civilians were `` at the behest of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'' but <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> has denied the allegation. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Pakistani officials estimate that bombs planted by Afghan agents have killed more than 400 civilians in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. The bloodiest incident occurred in July 1987 when three car bombs exploded in the main bazaar of <LOCATION> Karachi </LOCATION>, killing 72 and injuring 260. The report said it is likely that the Soviets have been aware of Afghan operations in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> because of the close ties between WAD and the Soviet intelligence agency, <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION>. It said that while some of the material for the explosive devices can be purchased on the black market, other items can be obtained only through Soviet sources. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> estimates that about 1,500 Soviet advisers work with WAD.
