<HEAD>Drought-Stricken Iowa Farmers Go A-Haying To Idaho</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROGER MUNNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Farmers leaving for 10 days of harvesting free hay in <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> boarded buses in a downpour Monday, providing hope that their own drought-ravaged pastures might be green by the time they get home. `` But it will still take several weeks for that forage to grow back up, assuming we get enough rain, and even then you wonder what kind of growth there will be,'' said <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, manager of the <ORGANIZATION> Farm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Spokesman </ORGANIZATION>, a publication of the <ORGANIZATION> Iowa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION>. `` The drought has killed off part of it, and then if you have a frost the first part of October, that will curb things a little bit, too,'' he said. About 60 farmers boarded two chartered buses for the trip, hoping to harvest a train load of hay from reserve acreage. `` A lot of these guys really need the hay, so they made a quick decision to come. Some people hired people to go in their place,'' <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said. The venture is a cooperative effort of the <ORGANIZATION> Farm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, with Greyhound donating the buses, <LOCATION> Burlington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> railroad donating freight space for the baled hay and three banks in <LOCATION> Chariton </LOCATION>, south of <LOCATION> Des </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Moines </LOCATION>, putting up cash for meals along the way. <PERSON> Murdock </PERSON> said he expects other banks will also chip in. In spite of the donated services, organizer <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Murdock </PERSON> said he initially had trouble recruiting a crew for the excursion because the drought has made it even more difficult for farmers to leave home for extended periods. <PERSON> Murdock </PERSON>, a regional