<HEAD>Drought-Stricken Farmers Reminded of Reserve Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Farmers hit hard by this year's drought should think about enrolling highly erodible cropland in the long-term Conservation Reserve Program, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Monday. The current signup period for the <ORGANIZATION> CRP </ORGANIZATION> will end on Aug. 31. More than 25.5 million acres have been enrolled in previous signups, and the goal is to have 40 million to 45 million acres in the program by the end of 1990. Under the program, farmers offer bids to take land from crop production and plant it to grass or trees for 10 years as a guard against erosion. In return, they get federal assistance to pay for up to half of the cost of establishing the protective cover, plus annual rental payments for the <ORGANIZATION> CRP </ORGANIZATION> land. <PERSON> Vern </PERSON> <PERSON> Neppl </PERSON>, acting executive vice president of the department's <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, said farmers may bid to enroll eligible land that has not been harvested in 1988 due to drought `` If their bids are accepted, the producers will receive their first CRP rental payments in 1988,'' <PERSON> Neppl </PERSON> said. `` Also, they will be guaranteed payments for nine more years, an additional source of income regardless of weather condition during those years.'' Cropland that has been hayed in counties approved for drought relief is eligible for the <ORGANIZATION> CRP </ORGANIZATION> if it meets program requirements, but there may be a reduction in the 1988 payment, <PERSON> Neppl </PERSON> said. Producers also have the option of enrolling land for 1989. Enrollment of erodible land in the <ORGANIZATION> CRP </ORGANIZATION> will help farmers meet the conservation provisions of the 1985 farm law, <PERSON> Neppl </PERSON> said. Those require producers to have an approved conservation plan for erodible land in place by Jan. 1, 1990, to