<HEAD>13 Arabs Wounded, Abu Nidal Claims Responsibility for Grenade
Attack</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Israeli troops shot and wounded 13 Arabs Monday during a strike called to protest Israeli tax raids. The Palestinian guerrilla group led by <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Nidal </PERSON> claimed responsibility for a bombing in the city of <LOCATION> Haifa </LOCATION> that injured 25 people. A Palestinian also died of wounds suffered in a clash with troops a day earlier, bringing to 252 the Arab death toll in the eight-month rebellion in Israeli-occupied territories. Four Israelis have died. The worst violence erupted in the coastal <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>, where troops opened fire to disperse hundreds of stone-throwing protesters at the Shati and Jabaliya refugee camps, Arab hospital officials said. Eleven Palestinians ranging in age from 11 to 21 were shot and wounded in the clashes, the hospital officials said. Two suffered serious injuries and were transferred to an Israeli hospital. Two protesters were also shot and wounded in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>, one in the town of <LOCATION> Nur </LOCATION> <LOCATION> el </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Shams </LOCATION> and one in the town of <LOCATION> Zawiyeh </LOCATION>. The army imposed a curfew on <LOCATION> Nablus </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>'s largest city, and surrounding refugee camps following violent protests overnight. Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>, meanwhile, condemned as an `` outrageous terrorist act'' the grenade attack Saturday night on a crowded pedestrian mall in <LOCATION> Haifa </LOCATION>. Twenty-five people were wounded in the bombing, including an 8-year-old boy who lost his left leg below the knee. Four Palestinians from the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> city of <LOCATION> Jenin </LOCATION> are being held in connection with the attack. In a statement published Monday in the <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> newspaper An-Nahar, <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Nidal </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Fatah-Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> claimed responsibility for the attack, saying it was in revenge for the April 16 assassination of <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> military commander <PERSON> Khalil </PERSON> <PERSON> Wazir </PERSON>, also known as <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Jihad </PERSON>. Israeli officials have acknowledged privately that <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> carried out the assassination. <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>, head of the right-wing <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> bloc, told <ORGANIZATION> Israel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> radio </ORGANIZATION> the <LOCATION> Haifa </LOCATION> attack `` shows again that this struggle -LRB- the uprising -RRB- ... is not for certain territories under Israeli rule, but against the security and existence of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>.'' But <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>'s political rival, Foreign Minister <PERSON> Shimon </PERSON> <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> of the left-of-center <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, said the attack was not linked to the uprising. `` I think this has nothing to do with the intefadeh -LRB- Arabic for uprising -RRB-,'' <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> radio </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> activists denied <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>'s claim that the goal of the uprisng was to eliminate <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. `` The purpose of the intefadeh is not to destroy <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> or the <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> people, but to establish a <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> state and end the occupation,'' read leaflets distributed Monday in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>. The leaflets, written in <LOCATION> Hebrew </LOCATION> and Arabic, also called on <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> soldiers to refuse service in the occupied lands. In <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION>, wall posters appeared overnight expressing <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> defiance of harsh Israeli measures against firebomb throwers, including house demolitions and deportations. `` We're not afraid. Our young will continue to throw firebombs,'' said the posters, which showed youths hurling stones and bottles at Israeli jeeps. Streets were deserted and stores shuttered in the occupied lands Monday, the second day of a strike called by undergropund leaders to protest raids in which Israelis confiscate property of Arabs refusing to pay taxes. Tax boycotts have been a key source of resistance to Israeli rule during the uprising. A court extended the detention of two Israeli Jews suspected of setting fire to a shack near <LOCATION> Tel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aviv </LOCATION>, killing three Palestinians. A fistfight broke out outside the courthouse when the suspects scuffled with a television cameraman, breaking his camera, <ORGANIZATION> Israel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> radio </ORGANIZATION> said. <PERSON> Ahmad </PERSON> <PERSON> Sharnobi </PERSON>, 22, of the Askar refugee camp near <LOCATION> Nablus </LOCATION> died Monday of a bullet wound in the stomach. He was shot Sunday night by plainclothes Israeli agents. The army confirmed the death and said security forces had entered the camp to try to prevent expected riots during a strike.
