<HEAD>Burundi at a Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Burundi Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Here are some facts and figures about <LOCATION> Burundi </LOCATION>:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 THE LAND _ <LOCATION> Burundi </LOCATION> covers 10,759 square miles, about the size of <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>. It is astride the main Nile-Congo dividing crest, bounded on the west by the narrow plain of the <LOCATION> Ruzizi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tanganyika </LOCATION>. The interior is a broken plateau at an average altitude of about 5,000 feet, sloping eastward to <LOCATION> Tanzania </LOCATION> and the valley of the <LOCATION> Maragarazi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. Its neighbors are <LOCATION> Zaire </LOCATION> on the west, <LOCATION> Rwanda </LOCATION> on the north and <LOCATION> Tanzania </LOCATION> on the east.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 THE PEOPLE _ <LOCATION> Burundi </LOCATION> is densely populated with 5 million people, of whom 84 percent are of the Hutu tribe. Although the Tutsi make up only 15 percent of the population, they control the army and government.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 THE ECONOMY _ Some nickel deposits still are exploited but <LOCATION> Burundi </LOCATION>'s main economic activity, and the main source of employment, is subsistence agriculture. Beans, kassava, maize, peanuts, peas, sorghum and bananas are grown but the main cash crop is coffee, which accounts for 90 percent of exports. There has been little industrial development.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 HISTORY _ Tradition recounts the establishment of a Tutsi kingdom as early as the 16th century. <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> occupied the country in 1890 and incorporated it into <LOCATION> German </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. In 1919 it became part of <LOCATION> Ruanda-Urundi </LOCATION>, administsered by <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>, first as a League of Nations mandate and then as a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> trust territory. It became independent in 1962 and has had several governments, the most recent ones military.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
