<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Syndicated columnist <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rowan </PERSON> probably had been told he did not have to register a revolver he used to shoot a teen-ager trespassing in his yard, the city government's top lawyer says However, city officials on Monday refused to drop charges against <PERSON> Rowan </PERSON>, who has written in favor of gun control. He was charged with possession of an unregistered handgun and ammunition after wounding a youth who had been taking an unauthorized predawn swim in his backyard swimming pool June 14. <PERSON> Rowan </PERSON> has claimed that the weapon was given to him in 1982 by his son, <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agent. Both Rowans have steadfastly maintained that city officials instructed them that the gun did not have to be registered, since <PERSON> Rowan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> was a federal agent. That was buttressed by a memo written Aug. 11 from <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION> Counsel <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooke </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> to Police Chief <PERSON> Maurice </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON>, indicating that some police officers have erred in enforcing the gun registration law. `` It has come to my attention that some officers in the <ORGANIZATION> MPD </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- have interpreted the provision so as to exempt from registration firearms owned by <ORGANIZATION> MPD </ORGANIZATION> officers or other law enforcement officers,'' <PERSON> Cooke </PERSON> wrote <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> in the memo, obtained by The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> on Monday. `` I understand further that when an officer ceases to be an MPD or other law enforcement officer this ` exempt' status is not revoked and the former officer is not required to surrender the weapon.'' The city's far-reaching 1976 handgun ordinance, which requires that all weapons purchased after that date be registered with the city, should be amended to make clear that law enforcement officers are not exempt from this regulation, <PERSON> Cooke </PERSON> concluded. `` Police were telling people that once they left any police force, they did n't have to register the weapon,'' said <PERSON> Raoul </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carroll </PERSON>, <PERSON> Rowan </PERSON>'s attorney. `` The memo makes that clear.'' The document was included in material <PERSON> Carroll </PERSON> submitted to <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in hopes of getting the charges dismissed. <PERSON> Beverly </PERSON> <PERSON> Burke </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for <PERSON> Cooke </PERSON>, said city officials still intend to prosecute the columnist. She would not comment on the memo, which she described as `` private, not something that should be in the public domain.'' Police also declined to comment. Efforts to reach <PERSON> Rowan </PERSON> for comment were not immediately successsful. <PERSON> Rowan </PERSON>'s trial has been set for Sept. 22. If convicted of possessing an unregistered weapon and ammunition, he could receive up to one year in jail and a $ 1,000 fine on each count.
