<HEAD>Pentagon Seeking Money For Airplane `Recognition' System</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> has asked <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to restore government financing for research on advanced airplane `` recognition'' systems of a type that might have prevented the shootdown of an Iranian airliner by a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> cruiser. Such systems, if proven feasible, could make it easier for radar centers on the ground or at sea to identify the types of planes they detect _ for example, distinguishing between a jet fighter and a cargo plane. The funding request was presented formally by <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, the assistant defense secretary for command, control, communications and intelligence systems, just two weeks after the <ORGANIZATION> USS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vincennes </ORGANIZATION> on July 3 shot down an Iranian A-300 Airbus carrying 290 people that the cruiser mistook for a F-14 fighter jet. In a letter to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Appropriations committees, <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> urged <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to restore $ 9.2 million for research and development of so-called `` non-cooperative target-recognition systems.'' <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> had cut the money from the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s fiscal 1989 budget bill after discovering the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> were not prepared to commit themselves to continuing the research in fiscal 1990 and beyond. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> says it made a decision to scrap a five-year research program in the field because of the overall Pentagon budget squeeze. `` It is requested that consideration be given to a floor amendment to restore the requested $ 9.2 million in <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> funding for non-cooperative identification efforts,'' <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> wrote on July 18. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> made no reference to the <LOCATION> Vincennes </LOCATION> incident, but added: `` The <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> is striving to develop aircraft identification systems to provide effective control of our increasingly lethal air defense weapons. This is not an easy problem; however, there is a non-cooperative identification technique which has the potential to identify hostile and civil aircraft.'' Non-cooperative identification is military slang for any system that does n't rely on aircraft radio emissions to make an identification. So-called cooperative systems, now in use by most air forces, involve one plane determining whether another is friendly by `` asking'' for a special radio transmission. The <LOCATION> Vincennes </LOCATION>, in mistakenly classifying the Iranian airliner as a hostile jet fighter, apparently made a mistake in the way it interpreted that plane's radio signal response. A non-cooperative system attempts to identify an airplane without asking for a radio transmission. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, in his letter, did not include any details of the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> research because he said the work was classified. But he did say a new non-cooperative system `` has been tested on one ship with very good results.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> already has responded to <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>'s plea by agreeing to provide the research money. The House has yet to act, however, and the prospects for restoring the money still are uncertain.
