<TEXT>
 Gravediggers in northern <LOCATION> Burundi </LOCATION> have counted the bodies of about 5,000 people massacred in battles between members of the <PERSON> Hutu </PERSON> and <PERSON> Tutsi </PERSON> tribes, government officials said Monday. Government and <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> officials in neighboring <LOCATION> Rwanda </LOCATION> said at least 35,000 Burundians crossed the border into <LOCATION> Rwanda </LOCATION> to escape the slaughter last week. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said no Americans were in the areas of the killings. Foreign Minister <PERSON> Cyprien </PERSON> <PERSON> Mbonimpa </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Burundi </LOCATION> included the first official death toll in an official communique issued at a morning briefing for diplomats. It also was read during the 1 p.m. newscast on government radio, according to diplomats who spoke in telephone interviews from <LOCATION> Bujumbura </LOCATION>, capital of the small, densely populated country in Central Africa. They asked that their names not be used. `` It said the people in charge of burying the bodies have counted approximately 5,000,'' a Western diplomat said, but whether that was the total dead was not unknown immediately. `` It appeared as if they had concluded their work, but it was not at all clear,'' he said. `` The facts are very, very unclear and sketchy because of the remoteness of the area.'' He said there appeared to have been no major violence since about 24 hours after the fighting began Aug. 14 between the Hutu, <LOCATION> Burundi </LOCATION>'s majority tribe, and the <PERSON> Tutsi </PERSON>, the minority tribe that controls the military and government. Members of the Hutu and <PERSON> Tutsi </PERSON> tribes are old enemies. After a coup attempt in 1972 in the former <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION> colony, the Tutsi massacred 100,000-300 ,000 Hutu, including most of the tribe's intelligentsia, according to human rights `` The news did n't start coming down to <LOCATION> Bujumbura </LOCATION> until late Tuesday and Wednesday,'' the diplomat said. `` The army went in on Tuesday and got things under control fairly quickly.'' <PERSON> Mbonimpa </PERSON>, the foreign minister, described a media report that at least 24,000 people were killed as `` highly exaggerated,'' another diplomat said, and `` from every report, including those from non-governmental sources, no one believes that figure.'' Neighboring <LOCATION> Rwanda </LOCATION>'s state radio said Monday that 35,000 people had crossed the border. <LOCATION> Rwanda </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Burundi </LOCATION>, former Belgian colonies, are among the world's most densely populated countries. Rwandan officials said resources were being strained by the influx of refugees. In <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION> said they would send a planeload of tents, blankets and other emergency aid for the refugees worth the equivalent of more than $ 700,000. According to <LOCATION> Rwanda </LOCATION>'s official radio, monitored in <LOCATION> Nairobi </LOCATION>, officials of the neighboring country met Sunday at the border town of <LOCATION> Butare </LOCATION>, where the refugees were gathered. It gave no details. <LOCATION> Burundi </LOCATION> claims last week's violence was caused by expatriate Hutus who infiltrated northern <LOCATION> Burundi </LOCATION> from foreign countries and incited Hutus to massacre Tutsis. The <ORGANIZATION> Hutu </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, an exiled opposition group, accused the Tutsi-dominated military of massacring thousands of Hutus, but diplomatic sources said there was no evidence of that. More than 90 percent of the population is Hutu in the northern area around the <LOCATION> Marangara </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ntega </LOCATION> rural communes, where most of last week's killings occurred. <LOCATION> Burundi </LOCATION>'s communique said the government had the situation under control and the military, the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Progress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> party </ORGANIZATION> and the bureaucracy had been ordered to `` show restraint,'' one of the diplomats said. `` It said the policy of the government was one of respect for human rights and of ethnic reconciliation,'' he reported. Maj. <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Buyoya </PERSON>'s government has restricted travel between towns and is not allowing trips into the north, the diplomats said. A 7 p.m. to 5 a.m. curfew is in force throughout the country and meetings of more than five people are prohibited. The tribal battles were the first significant violence reported in <LOCATION> Burundi </LOCATION> since <PERSON> Buyoya </PERSON> seized power in a bloodless coup Sept. 3, 1987, while then-President <PERSON> Jean-Baptiste </PERSON> <PERSON> Bagaza </PERSON> was abroad. Nearly 5 million people live in <LOCATION> Burundi </LOCATION>, which is about the size of <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>. Its population is 84 percent <PERSON> Hutu </PERSON> and 15 percent <PERSON> Tutsi </PERSON>. Roughly the same tribal proportions apply in <LOCATION> Rwanda </LOCATION>, which is slightly smaller than <LOCATION> Burundi </LOCATION>.
