<HEAD>Judge Hears Statistical Evidence in FBI Discrimination Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOLDEN LEWIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EL PASO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> opened its defense Monday in a discrimination trial by presenting four hours of statistics designed to show that Hispanics are promoted as rapidly and disciplined as fairly as other <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agents. `` Hispanics have no problem getting into management,'' Dr. <PERSON> Rebecca </PERSON> <PERSON> Klemm </PERSON>, an independent statistical consultant, testified. `` They get what they ask for in terms of promotions.'' The 311 Hispanic agents who joined in the class-action suit in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> contend the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> discriminates against Hispanics in hiring, promoting, disciplining and assignments. They want damages and changes in <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> policies. About 400 of the bureau's 9,000 agents are Hispanic During the first week of testimony, about 40 <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agents testified that Hispanics are transferred more often to undesirable offices, are given more assignments that are either less glamorous or more dangerous and receive less recognition for their successes. The <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> opened the second week of the trial with Ms. <PERSON> Klemm </PERSON>, who disputed findings of Dr. <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> LaFree </PERSON>, a sociologist at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mexico </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> LaFree </PERSON> testified last week that Hispanic <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agents are less likely to hold higher-level jobs. Ms. <PERSON> Klemm </PERSON> used the same raw numbers culled from the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> as <PERSON> LaFree </PERSON> but reached different conclusions. <PERSON> LaFree </PERSON> testified last week that 15 percent of Hispanic <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agents with at least five years of agency experience are managers, compared with 21 percent of non-Hispanic <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agents with the same level of experience. Ms. <PERSON> Klemm </PERSON> testified that <PERSON> Hispanics </PERSON> have done better head-to-head against <ORGANIZATION> Anglo </ORGANIZATION> agents when competing against them for promotions _ that 14.4 percent of Hispanics got such promotions versus 10.5 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Anglo </ORGANIZATION> agents applying for the jobs. She did not say how many people from each ethnic background applied for competitive promotions. She said Hispanics have an average of about two years less experience than their <ORGANIZATION> Anglo </ORGANIZATION> counterparts when they attain the bottom rung of the management ladder in the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>. `` In terms of career advancement, they advance timely,'' she testified. `` Therefore, even if they do different things as Hispanic agents, they do fine as far as advancement.'' The suit was filed in January 1987 by <PERSON> Bernardo </PERSON> `` <PERSON> Matt </PERSON><PERSON> '' </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON>, who contends he was forced by superiors in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and elsewhere to accept demotions he did n't deserve. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON>, now the No. 2 agent in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paso </LOCATION>, used to be in charge of the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Juan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>, office and was second-in-command in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> before his transfer to <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paso </LOCATION>. The non-jury trial is expected to end Friday and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Lucius </PERSON> <PERSON> Bunton </PERSON> is expected to reach a decision within six months. Federal employees are not entitled to jury trials when suing the government in discrimination cases. Hispanic activists have said a multitude of discrimination trials could result if the plaintiffs win. <PERSON> Hugo </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agent and the co-counsel for the plaintiffs, has compared the case to those fought by blacks in the'60s and by women in the'70s.
