<HEAD>AFL-CIO To Seek Restrictions On Polish Exports</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> said Monday it will petition the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration to restrict Polish exports to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> markets under provisions in the new trade bill that are designed to safeguard workers' rights. `` We certainly believe the worker rights provisions of the trade legislation should be applied in the case of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>,'' said <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Lane </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirkland </PERSON>. `` They should be denied access to the American market under those provisions since they are in violation of worker rights.'' <PERSON> Kirkland </PERSON> made the comments on Monday as the Polish government ordered troops to secure major industrial plants and clamped curfews on three provinces hit by pro-Solidarity strikes following a week of the worst labor unrest since 1981. The trade bill <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> is to sign Tuesday in a ceremony before <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, dockworkers includes a provision permitting the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade representative to retaliate against countries that deny worker rights such as recognition of free trade unions. <PERSON> Kirkland </PERSON> said he was told by the <ORGANIZATION> Polish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> here last week that his request for a visa to visit the country had been turned down for a third time. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> last year imported some $ 261.5 million in products from <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, primarily canned meat, fish, plates of iron steel, nails, clothing and glassware. <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> officials said the retaliation that the federation would seek from the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration could take several forms, including revoking <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s most-favored-nation status as a trading partner. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration revoked that status in 1981 upon the imposition of martial law in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> but gradually restored it, with the <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION>'s approval, after martial law was ended. Revocation of most-favored status would raise the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> tariffs on imports from <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. For canned pork, as an example, the tariff would jump from a penny a pound to 3.25 cents a pound. The tariff on cast iron pipes would jump from 8 percent to 25 percent. Also Monday, the <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> elected new <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON> as a vice president of the federation and to a seat on its policy-setting executive council. <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON> fills the vacancy on the 35-member board left by the death last month of his predecessor at the Teamster's helm, <PERSON> Jackie </PERSON> <PERSON> Presser </PERSON>.
