<HEAD>Heavy Rain in Plains, Record Cold in Parts of Northeast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The summer of 1988 took an uncharacteristic turn Monday as thunderstorms dumped heavy rain on parts of the <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION> and overnight temperatures hit record lows in parts of the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION>. Storms buffeted several Plains states with gusty winds and heavy rain, helping to replenish some drought-sapped soil and causing some isolated flooding in parts of <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>. In northwest <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Sioux </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> recorded over 6 -LCB- inches of rain overnight and Monday morning. The downpour pushed the <LOCATION> Floyd </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> at least 1 foot above flood stage in places and caused minor lowland flooding. Several other locations in that corner of the state reported at least 3 inches of rain by morning. `` It might help the lawns some,'' said <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> <PERSON> Hora </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Growers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. `` And the football fields will be green. But the corn is history.'' The rain should help late-maturing bean crops and activate herbicides, preventing carryover chemical damage next season, <PERSON> Hora </PERSON> said. Elsewhere in <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Des </PERSON> <PERSON> Moines </PERSON> got an inch and two-thirds of rain in the six hours ended at 2 p.m. EDT while <LOCATION> Waterloo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ottumwa </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Cedar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rapids </ORGANIZATION> had about 1 \ inches St. Cloud, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>, recorded 1 -LCB- inches in the same period. Morning thunderstorm winds gusted to 63 mph at the <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Neb. </LOCATION>, airport. Midday showers and thunderstorms also hit northeast <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>, northwest <LOCATION> Kan