<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A senior <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> cleric said Monday the holders of foreign hostages in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> should stick to their demands `` until death.'' <PERSON> Sheik </PERSON> <PERSON> Sobhi </PERSON> <PERSON> Tufaili </PERSON> spoke to 25,000 <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> faithful marking the death of the Shiite Moslems' most revered saint, Imam <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON>. In a clear reference to <LOCATION> Islamic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jihad </LOCATION>, the group that holds at least two American hostages, <PERSON> Tufaili </PERSON> said: `` I turn to those holding the prisoners -LRB- foreign captives -RRB- in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, although we do not accept to hold the hostages. I tell them: Adhere to your demands. Do not let go of them or retreat until death.'' Demands made by Islamic Jihad, or Islamic Holy War, include release of prisoners form Arab and foreign prisons, release of Lebanese and Palestinians from <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> jails and withdrawal of <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> troops from south <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. It has specifically demanded freedom for 17 Shiites imprisoned in <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> for bombing the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and French embassies there in 1983. <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION>, or Party of God, has <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s support and is widely believed to be the umbrella organization for <ORGANIZATION> Shiite </ORGANIZATION> extremist groups holding most of the 18 foreigners missing in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, who include nine Americans. Held longest is <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, chief <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> correspondent of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, who was kidnapped March 16, 1985. <PERSON> Tufaili </PERSON> closed his remarks by declaring to hostage holders: `` You must protect them -LRB- the demands -RRB- by all means.'' Listeners in the ancient city of <LOCATION> Baalbek </LOCATION> beat their chests with fists and chanted: `` God Is Great!'' <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON>, the Shiites' martyr, and a group of his followers were massacred in 680 in what is now the <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> province of <LOCATION> Karbala </LOCATION> in a leadership fight between Moslem factions. Moslems subsequently formed the Shiite and Sunni sects of the faith. Other parades and observances were held Monday in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s southern slums and in <LOCATION> south </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, where thousands of Shiites slashed their heads with razors or beat themselves with swords, axes or iron bars Blood dripped from the faces and chests of men and children as they re-enacted the killing of <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON>. No deaths were reported in the special parades, known as Ashoura. In southern <LOCATION> Nabatiyeh </LOCATION>, traditionally the focal point of the Ashoura, 50,000 people gathered in the main square to re-enact the killing. Afterward, scores sliced themselves with razors and clubbed themselves with swords or axes. Some lost consciousness and were taken to hospitals for treatment. In southern <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Sheik </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> <PERSON> Fadlallah </PERSON> delivered a sermon to mark the anniversary. He is the sect's most influential cleric in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> and the reputed spiritual guide of <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION>, or Party of God. <PERSON> Fadlallah </PERSON> gave his sermon in the air-conditioned Bir el-Abed Mosque. The hostages, who include nine Americans, are widely believed held in <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Hay </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Madi </LOCATION> barracks building, about 10 blocks from the mosque. <PERSON> Fadlallah </PERSON> omit