went to a private school,'' the elder <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said of his son, who graduated in 1969 from <ORGANIZATION> DePauw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> a small liberal arts college in <LOCATION> Greencastle </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, in a telephone interview, conceded that his son `` had n't put his academic skills together'' while at <ORGANIZATION> DePauw </ORGANIZATION> `` He was no Mensa, but it was his thought that he probably got a better education because they had much smaller classrooms and the curriculum was defined for them,'' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said. `` Somehow he convinced them.'' The young <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s personality also helped gain him a spot in 1970 on the staff of Attorney General <PERSON> Theodore </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sendak </PERSON>, according to <LOCATION> Medford </LOCATION> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, who was instrumental in directing the aspiring lawyer to the Statehouse job. `` I think he probably got himself hired in the interviews,'' said <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, a former editor, political columnist and editor at the <PERSON> Pulliam </PERSON> family owned <ORGANIZATION> Indianapolis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>. `` <PERSON> Danny </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> was an impressive young kid.'' `` I would guess they -LRB- <PERSON> Sendak </PERSON>'s staff -RRB- would take a look at academic records but I think they would be influenced also by how he handles himself,'' <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> said. `` This is an office that dealt with the public.'' <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, who now is a staff member of the Washington-based <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journalism </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, denied that family members pulled strings for the <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> senator, who worked his way through law school. `` If the <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> famil