<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The nation's largest labor federation said Monday it would call a strike by its 3.5 million members next month to protest the economic policies of President <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON>. The walkout was scheduled for early September but an exact date will not be set until later this week, said <PERSON> Saul </PERSON> <PERSON> Ubaldini </PERSON>, secretary-general of the General Labor Confederation. The one-day general strike would be the 12th walkout organized by the labor group since <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON> took office in December 1983. A march by thousands of workers in the capital also is planned. The strike is being called to protest government economic policies that union leaders say have caused serious inflation and eroded the purchasing power of workers. Most Argentine unions belong to the federation. Its 11 previous general strikes have been peaceful and fairly successful, shutting down government offices and public transportation, although private businesses have remained open. The cost of living rose 178 percent during the first seven months of this year. After it increased 25.6 percent in July, <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON> devalued the austral by 11.4 percent against the dollar, implemented budget cuts and instituted a system of voluntary price controls. Wages have not kept pace with inflation, and prices continue rising despite voluntary controls. The labor federation has demanded an increase in the minimum monthly wage, from the current $ 66 to $ 121. The federation on Friday rejected the government's offer to boost the minimum wage to $ 79. <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON> is asking the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> for $ 1.2 billion and the success of his economic recovery plan is a key issue in the May presidential and legislative elections. <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> has a $ 56 billion foreign debt. Half of the 254 seats in the <ORG