<HEAD>Bush, Dukakis Begin Using Federal Funds For General Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Democrat <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and Republican <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> are delving into the $ 92 million taxpayer-funded trough for the general election, with <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> getting to his share first. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> got a headstart on <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> by receiving his party's nomination almost a month before the Republicans formally picked <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> last week That meant he got his $ 46.1 million from the federal <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> earlier and has already spent $ 1.8 million, according to July financial reports available Monday at the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, however, has wasted no time in laying the groundwork for his general election campaign. He had borrowed money against the $ 46.1 million he stood to receive once he became the official nominee. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had spent $ 672,570 on his general election effort as of the end of July, his financial report shows. He borrowed money he raised during the primary campaign for his `` compliance fund,'' used for expenses to comply with election law administrative requirements. Unlike the primary campaign, the candidates do not have to raise money privately for the general election. They receive $ 46.1 million from the federal fund that is supported by the voluntary $ 1 checkoff on individual tax returns. As the general election campaign gets under way, the candidates have invested heavily in polling and in media production for ads that will be used between now and November. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> invested more than $ 300,000 in polling last month. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has been spending more money getting ready for the TV wars, paying more than $ 127,000 during July for media production and consulting to the firm of his media consultant <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Ailes </PERSON>. In addition to what the candidates are allotted, the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> and Democratic party organizations can spend $ 8.3 million each to help elect their nominees. The limit applies to direct spending, but the parties also have devised other ways to indirectly help their tickets, through use of so-called soft money for generic party activity. Those efforts will result in spending many times the limit on direct party support. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> closed out the last month of his primary campaign having spent $ 21.7 million against the federally imposed $ 23 million limit on primary spending, his reports showed. He still owed $ 469,000 in outstanding bills, and his campaign committee was owed nearly that much in receiveables. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who was scrimping to keep from topping the limit by the end of the campaign, was up to $ 22.6 million against the $ 23 million cap at the end of July. He was owed $ 255,183 and had $ 61,446 in debts.
