<FIRST>r w AM-YouthSurvey     08-22 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Youth Survey,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study: American Youth `Staying Younger Longer'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CRISPIN Y. CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Young people in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> are living at home longer, marrying later and taking more time to become self-sufficient, according to a government report released Monday. Assistant Education Secretary <PERSON> Chester </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Finn </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> said the study of youth aged 14 to 24 indicates they are `` staying younger longer.'' `` They seem to be becoming autonomous, self-supporting individuals at a slower rate than was once the case,'' <PERSON> Finn </PERSON> said. The report, titled `` Youth Indicators: Trends in the Well-Being of American Youth,'' was compiled from information that had been collected since 1950 at federal agencies and private organizations. <PERSON> Finn </PERSON> said the figures show young people `` are living with their parents longer and they are slower to form their own families.'' `` A number of indicators suggest that the transition from childhood to adulthood is taking longer and presenting more pitfalls than was the case several years ago,'' the study said. `` Youths in the 20s are living at home measurably longer; since 1970, they have been delaying marriage to significantly later ages; and since 1980, they have found their average earnings declining while those of older workers have increased.'' Among the findings: _ The share of youth aged 18 to 24 who lived with their parents or in college dormitories rose from 43 percent in 1960 to 53.6 percent in 1985. _ The number of first marriages per 1,000 never-married women aged 20 to 24 fell from 220.1 in 1970 to 104.4 in 1984. _ Median income for women aged 20 to 24 fell from $ 12,517 in 1980 to $ 12,192 in 1986, using constant 1986 dollars. The comparable figures for young men fell from $ 16,113 in 1970 to $ 14,152 in 1986. The study said the trends may be related, since `` late marriage is a reasonable response to lower earnings; living with parents is a reasonable arrangement for those not earning enough to support themselves.'' <PERSON> Finn </PERSON> said the report also showed falling scores on college entrance examinations and a last-place ranking for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> students in recent international science and mathematics tests, raising concern about how the youth will fare in the future. `` Compared to kids elsewhere in the world they are performing poorly on all kinds of tests and that makes me worry,'' he said. `` They make me worry about the future of a country that's raising up people with a number of years in school but that do n't know anything.''
</TEXT>
