<HEAD>Foreign Minister Denies U.S. Harassment Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAFAEL CANDANEDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Foreign Minister <PERSON> Jorge </PERSON> <PERSON> Ritter </PERSON> on Monday denied charges that Panamanian forces are harassing <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military personnel, calling the allegations an escalation of a campaign to undermine the government. <PERSON> Ritter </PERSON> told a news conference <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials who accused the government of encouraging attacks on Americans were seeking `` an excuse ... -LRB- for -RRB- new and more aggressive measures against <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>.'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> said Sunday that <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> personnel reported at least 240 incidents of harassment by Panamanian officials this year, ranging from extortion for traffic violations to the blocking of mail. The <ORGANIZATION> Panama </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION> rejected the allegations Sunday night and said in a statement that <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> troops caused problems for Panamanian authorities, including fights, mistreatment of women and shooting in public places. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration has applied economic sanctions against <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> in an effort to force the ouster of Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, commander of the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION> and the country's de facto ruler. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> is under <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> indictment in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> on drug trafficking and money laundering charges, which he denies. <PERSON> Ritter </PERSON> said Monday American officials made the allegations to make it appear that `` the -LRB- <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> -RRB- aggressors become the victims.'' He reiterated Panamanian charges that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was seeking a pretext to annul the 1977 <ORGANIZATION> Panama </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Canal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaties </ORGANIZATION>, under which the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is to hand over control of the canal to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> on Dec. 31, 1999. Col. <PERSON> Rogelio </PERSON> <PERSON> Alba </PERSON>, co-president of a bi-national committee charged with the defense of the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION>, said that <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> officials `` have shown a lack of respect in all things for us.'' <PERSON> Alba </PERSON> said, `` We've gone out of the way to collaborate with them. We've never interfered with them, and they're killing us with hunger.'' _ referring to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic sanctions that have crippled <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s economy. The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> on Sunday quoted <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Southern Command, <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> officials as saying there have been an increasing number of beatings, abductions, rape and extortion of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military personnel and their dependents. The story, under a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> dateline, said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials viewed the incidents as a campaign by the Panamanian government to pressure the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to lift sanctions. But one Southern Command official said Sunday the increased reports of harassment `` could be just an indication of individual frustration and anger.'' <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> imposed economic sanctions on <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> in March after the <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> ousted President <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Arturo </PERSON> <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON>. <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> has since been in hiding, but the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> continues to recognize him as <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s legitimate president. About 12,000 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> servicemen are stationed in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> by treaty to protect the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION>. They are attached to the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION>, which oversees all <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military operations south of the U.S.-Mexico border.
