<HEAD>Smoke Causes Evacuation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>REXBURG, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An explosion and fire at the pharmaceutical laboratory associated with Diet Center stores Monday sent clouds of smoke through this eastern <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> town, forcing the evacuation of a four-block-wide area. The blast occurred about 3 p.m. in the research and development laboratories at <ORGANIZATION> Ferguson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pharmaceutical </ORGANIZATION> while employees were on a break. No injuries were reported, said <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> <PERSON> Mayfield </PERSON>, operations director for the state <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disaster </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>. Residents and businesses within a two-block radius were evacuated, along with pupils and employees at a nearby elementary school, where classes were just ending. Most of the materials in the laboratory involved vitamins and diet supplements manufactured for the company's 2,300 <ORGANIZATION> Diet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> franchises in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Mayfield </PERSON> said. Authorities warned residents, however, that the smoke could contain toxic elements. <PERSON> Mayfield </PERSON> said this was because the fire burned plastic containers, releasing hazardous gases. About 120 employees worked in the laboratories, said <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferguson </PERSON>, co-founder of the Diet Centers with his wife, <PERSON> Sybil </PERSON>. The company had about a 60-day supply of stock in another building, said his son, <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferguson </PERSON>. The fire was expected to burn through the night, said <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Call </PERSON>, chief of the <ORGANIZATION> Idaho </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Falls </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, which was called for assi