<HEAD>Press Plane Accompanying Bush Makes Safe Emergency Landing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 9th graf, `It went...' with two grafs to UPDATE with
plane grounded, reporters taking another craft to Seattle; picks up
10th graf, `Key Air...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A chartered jet carrying about 80 reporters covering Republican presidential nominee <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was forced to dump fuel Monday and return to <LOCATION> O'Hare </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, officials said. `` It's taxiing to the terminal. There were no reports of injuries,'' said a supervisor at the O'Hare tower who would not be identified by name. He said the <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 727 landed without incident at 2:48 p.m. CDT. He was uncertain how far out of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> the aircraft was when it developed problems. `` They took off and they had a bad flap indicator,'' said <PERSON> Mort </PERSON> <PERSON> Edelstein </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. The reporters had covered the vice president's campaign stop in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, and were flying to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s next campaign stop at <LOCATION> Spokane </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>, authorities said. <PERSON> Edelstein </PERSON> said the decision to dump fuel while the plane circled over <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> preparing for an approach to <LOCATION> O'Hare </LOCATION> was routine. `` It's a precaution. When you make an emegency landing you do n't want to come in loaded, heavy with fuel,'' <PERSON> Edelstein </PERSON> said The plane was chartered from Key Air, based in <LOCATION> Rosslyn </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Missy </PERSON> <PERSON> Compton </PERSON>, a spokeswoman in <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> campaign office. `` It went back to <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. They have mechanics there in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> who are going to work on the plane,'' she said. Key Air officials decided Monday evening to ground the plane, and the reporters proceeded to <LOCATION> Spokane </LOCATION> on another aircraft, <PERSON> Edelstein </PERSON> said. Key Air Vice President <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Andrews </PERSON> said the flap problem was not serious and that the plane could have flown to <LOCATION> Spokane </LOCATION> if the captain had chosen to do so, though at a reduced altitude and speed. <PERSON> Andrews </PERSON> said the flaps on the plane's wings failed to go back to their normal position after takeoff. The incident was the second malfunction in the plane in three days, <PERSON> Andrews </PERSON> said. During <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s trip to <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> over the weekend, smoke entered the jet's cabin as the aircraft landed at <LOCATION> Port </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>. Airport officials said a hose came loose and allowed a small amount of smoke to leak, but said the problem was minor. The plane continued from <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION> on Saturday without incident, officials said.
