<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s rocky entry into big-league politics, stumbling over questions about his military record that threaten to overshadow <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s campaign, has left the exuberant young senator bloody but seemingly unbowed. Back in the nation's capital to prepare for his first solo campaign trip Wednesday, the <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> senator remains adamant that he is not an embarrassment to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, has not considered removing himself from the ticket, and sees nothing improper in the way he entered the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> at a time when other young men were marching off to fight in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>.
