<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Gravediggers in northern <LOCATION> Burundi </LOCATION> have counted the bodies of about 5,000 people massacred in battles between members of the <PERSON> Hutu </PERSON> and <PERSON> Tutsi </PERSON> tribes, government officials said Monday. Government and <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> officials in neighboring <LOCATION> Rwanda </LOCATION> said at least 35,000 Burundians crossed the border to escape the slaughter last week. Foreign Minister <PERSON> Cyprien </PERSON> <PERSON> Mbonimpa </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Burundi </LOCATION> included the first official death toll in an official communique issued at a morning briefing for diplomats. It also was read during the 1 p.m. newscast on government radio, according to diplomats who spoke in telephone interviews from <LOCATION> Bujumbura </LOCATION>, capital of the small, densely populated country in Central Africa. They asked that their names not be used. `` It said the people in charge of burying the bodies have counted approximately 5,000,'' a Western diplomat said, but whether that was the total dead was not unknown immediately. `` It appeared as if they had concluded their work, but it was not at all clear,'' he said. `` The facts are very, very unclear and sketchy because of the remoteness of the area.''
