<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After 34 years in power, President <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Colorado </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> is losing the loyalty of young people. Leaders say they are concerned but not alarmed. The trend is most evident in the universities, although no statistics are available to show the exact numbers of youths leaving or refusing to join the governing party. Student governments that formerly were staunchly pro-Stroessner now are dominated by coalitions that challenge the government. Students also are forming new groups. `` I'm a <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> by tradition, not conviction, because you have to be one to work as a public employee,'' said a 20-year-old law student who gave her name only as <PERSON> Maria </PERSON>. She added that she was fired from a government job for voting for an opposition slate of candidates for her student government. `` There is no doubt that the <ORGANIZATION> Colorado </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> has been losing influence among the young these days,'' said sociologist <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Nicolas </PERSON> <PERSON> Morinigo </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> Paraguayan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Students </ORGANIZATION>, which Education Minister <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortiz </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramirez </PERSON> describes as `` one more movement of irregular opposition to the government,'' was set up last year and comprises more than a dozen member groups. The <ORGANIZATION> Colorado </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> claims 1.4 million members, most of whom are younger than 29 and know no other president than <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON>, who took power by coup in 1954 and has ruled ever since. He is now 75 years old. The party, after the armed forces, is the strongest institution in this rural, landlocked nation of 3.8 million people. Membership is required for all public employees, and a prerequisite for benefits such as government scholarships. Desertions by youths and challenges by those who chart an independent course from within pose a thorny problem that <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> officials acknowlege they must address. A priority next year is `` the recovery of the diverse student centers that are circumstantially in the hands of the opposition,'' said <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Abdo </PERSON> <PERSON> Benitez </PERSON>, the party's vice president and <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON>'s longtime private secretary. `` We have made mistakes, but we are trying to set them right and give a greater dynamism to our policies with the young,'' said <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Chiola </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> congressman who is president of the party's <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Student Affairs. Students along with the <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> have called on the government to allow more civil rights and political liberties. In May, when Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> visited <LOCATION> Paraguay </LOCATION>, dozens of young people at a rally held up their arms, shackled at the wrists with handkerchiefs, to dramatize the lack of freedoms. In July, students boycotted classes at <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> to protest the expulsion of the Rev. <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> la </PERSON> <PERSON> Vega </PERSON>, a Spanish Jesuit priest who had lectured on Liberation Theology, a social reform movement among clergymen. Thousands of youths were among the estimated 20,000 people who in early August marched silently through the streets of the capital in a gesture of solidarity with the <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>, to which most Paraguayans at least nominally belong. The Rev. <PERSON> Dionisio </PERSON> <PERSON> Daeshague </PERSON>, who helped organize 14,000 youth volunteers for the papal visit, said dissident or independent student groups could be `` a time bomb for the government. All they need is someone to light the wick.'' Party leaders are concerned, but not alarmed. Militant <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON> supporters won control of the party at its convention last year. While that alienated some members, it nevertheless demonstrated that <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON>'s power base remains strong. `` Some of the youth call for democracy, but I do n't know what kind of democracy they want and demand because I consider this a democracy,'' said <PERSON> Zoraida </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramirez </PERSON>, vice president of the government-sanctioned <ORGANIZATION> Colorado </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Student </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. `` We have peace, we have progress with the government of President <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON>,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Ramirez </PERSON>, a 24-year-old economics student at <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. `` One has to leave the country to fully appreciate the peace in which we live.''
