<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Today is Sunday, Aug. 28, the 241st day of 1988. There are 125 days left in the year. Today's highlight in history: Twenty-five years ago, on Aug. 28, 1963, some 200,000 people participated in a peaceful civil rights rally in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, where they heard Dr. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> deliver his now-famous `` I Have a Dream'' speech in front of the Lincoln Memorial. On this date: In 1609, <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Hudson </PERSON> discovered <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>. In 1749, German author <PERSON> Johann </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolfgang </PERSON> <PERSON> von </PERSON> <PERSON> Goethe </PERSON> was born in <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>. In 1774, <PERSON> Mother </PERSON> <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Seton </PERSON>, the first American-born saint, was born in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. In 1828, Russian novelist <PERSON> Leo </PERSON> <PERSON> Tolstoy </PERSON> was born near <LOCATION> Tula </LOCATION>. In 1916, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s declaration of war against <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> took effect during World War I. In 1917, 10 suffragists were arrested as they picketed the White House. In 1922, radio station <ORGANIZATION> WEAF </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> aired the first radio commercial. -LRB- The <ORGANIZATION> Queensboro </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Realty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jackson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Heights </ORGANIZATION> paid $ 100 for 10 minutes of air time. -RRB- In 1968, police and anti-war demonstrators clashed in the streets of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> as the Democratic National Convention nominated <PERSON> Hubert </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON> for president. In 1973, more than 520 people died as a strong earthquake shook central <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. In 1981, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hinckley </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> pleaded innocent in a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, courtroom to charges of attempting to kill President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. In 1986, retired <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> warrant officer <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Whitworth </PERSON>, convicted for his role in a Soviet spy ring, was sentenced by a federal judge in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> to 365 years in prison. Ten years ago: Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> I </PERSON> took up the reins of papal power, reinstating the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> hierarchy of his predecessor, <PERSON> Pope </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> VI </PERSON>, who had died August 6. Five years ago: <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> Prime Minister <PERSON> Menachem </PERSON> <PERSON> Begin </PERSON>, reportedly despondent over the death of his wife and the rising casualty toll of <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> troops in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, announced his resignation. One year ago: A fire damaged the <LOCATION> Arcadia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, home of <PERSON> Ricky </PERSON>, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> and <PERSON> Randy </PERSON> <PERSON> Ray </PERSON>, three hemophiliac brothers infected with the AIDS virus whose court-ordered school attendance sparked a local uproar. -LRB- The Ray family ended up moving to <LOCATION> Sarasota </LOCATION>. -RRB- Movie director <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Huston </PERSON> died in <LOCATION> Middletown </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> R.I. </LOCATION>, at age 81. Today's birthdays: Actress <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Kulp </PERSON> is 67. Actor-dancer <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> is 63. Actor <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Gazzara </PERSON> is 58. Actor <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanders </PERSON> is 48. Actor <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Soul </PERSON> is 45. Sen. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Maine </LOCATION>, is 48. Baseball manager <PERSON> Lou </PERSON> <PERSON> Piniella </PERSON> is 45. Skating champion <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON> is 30. Thought for today: `` Time is too slow for those who wait, too swift for those who fear, too long for those who grieve, too short for those who rejoice. But for those who love, time is not.'' _ <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Dyke </PERSON>, <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> clergyman, poet and educator -LRB- 1852-1933 -RRB-.
