<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv23   08-22 0721</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 23,0740</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv23</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Tuesday, Aug. 23</NOTE>
<HEAD>A Refreshing Change: Take The Long-Term View</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 For a refreshing change, try the long-term economic view. It can relieve you of stress, improve your disposition, allow you to appreciate simple things like a good night's sleep, and probably put a few dollars in your pocket, too. While your neighbors in the game of financial survival cast furtive glances over their shoulders, your demeanor is carefree. Your smile and sturdy stride reflects not foolishness but confidence in your course. All the bad news bounces off your hide: Interest rates, the consumer price index, the balance of payments deficit, the budget deficit, the decline of your particular stocks. Warnings of future financial horrors worry you not. Good riddance to the daily worries; yours is the long-term view. Incredibly, the long-term investment view has been almost forgotten over the past year, although experience shows it is the only realistic way to view a portfolio. Investors have been caught, instead, in the game of trading. Traders try to outguess the market. They are nearsighted, so their view extends from a few hours to a few months. They calculate the value of their investments daily. They can see themselves as rich or poor in the same day. It is a nerve-wracking, mind-boggling, emotion-juggling experience, made all the worse by the realization that there is n't a thing that can be done to overcome the forces affecting the investments It is helplessness. In contrast, the long-run view requires little activity of any sort. It is easy on the nerves. And, while assurance of profit can never be accepted as a given, there is a very good chance the long-term investor will win out. It's in the cards, so to speak. Over the long-term, economic booms and busts cancel out each other, as do volatile swings in stock prices. Over time, sound stocks move in line with fundamental equity values. It's in the records. <ORGANIZATION> Wright </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investors </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> calculated the annual rates of return for the stocks in the <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Poor's 500-stock average for the past five years, and found this: Dividend income of 3.7 percent and earnings growth of 8.4 percent, for an earned retuurn of 12.1 percent. Changes in the price-earnings ratio for the 500 stocks added another 2.1 percent, for a total retuurn of 14.2 percent. While five years often includes a complete cycle of bull and bear markets, the latest five-year period is an exception. But, tracing the periods all the way back to 1929-1934, he found the annual return still came to 10.9 percent. After examining this evidence, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> projects that over the next five years, to June 30, 1993, we might reasonably expect an annual average of 3.5 percent dividend return and 7.7 percent earnings growth. Because current price-earnings ratios average somewhat higher than they have over the past 40 years, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> projected no growth in this sector. In fact, he deducted 0.6 percent, for a total annual return of 10.6 percent. These returns are averages, which means some quality stocks may perform even better, perhaps doubling in the next five-year period. But even if your stocks perform only to the average, you'd double your money in seven years. Seven years might seem like an age to those who have been focused on the next few weeks, but it is n't for some of the most respected and successful investors. They know they ca n't outguess the market; but they understand also that time and a growing American economy are on their side. In the long-term view, what might seem mountainous obstacles get reduced to specks. Even bear markets, terror of short-termers, are not feared. In fact, they're considered opportunities by patient investors. <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Perritt </PERSON>, editor of Investment Horizons, a newsletter, offers this long-term advice: `` Do not be frightened by bear markets. On the contrary, since they present a rare opportunity to accumulate the shares of good companies at bargain prices you should view bear markets in a favorable light. `` Remember, the only time you want stock prices to be at their peak is the day you plan to sell. In the meantime, you should be glad that the stock market periodically places its merchandise on sale.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv. PMs Tuesday, Aug. 23.</NOTE>
