<FIRST>a i AM-TiberRenaissance ADV31   08-22 0753</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tiber Renaissance, ADV31,0776</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv31</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed AMs, Aug. 31, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Tiber Lovers Try to Turn the Tide for Rome's Polluted River</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANCES D'EMILIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Smelly sewage notwithstanding, the <LOCATION> Tiber </LOCATION> is having a renaissance. Once the river was the lifeline of <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>. From ancient times to just a century ago, Romans bathed, fished and washed their clothes in it. <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>'s unplanned development boom after World War II, however, proved too much for the river. In 20 years, the population swelled from 1 million to more than 3 million. Anyone foolish enough to swim in the Tiber risks fatal infection from the untreated sewage that pours into it daily. Today's Romans do n't have the habit a going down to the river _ a stroll there means sidestepping broken bottles, rats and syringes discarded by drug addicts. But this summer gave Tiber lovers hope the tide is turning their way in the battle against pollution and neglect. With an eye on developing tourist attractions for 1990, when <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> hosts the World Cup soccer games, the city offered free boat rides during July. The response was so great that the promotion was extended into September. Tickets sold out for sunset cruises to the romantic setting of a play performed at the Roman amphitheater at <LOCATION> Ostia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antica </LOCATION>, the Tiber's ancient port. Hot, breezeless nights found young Romans playing cards and dancing on <LOCATION> Tiberina </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>. `` The fish will return, there will be pleasure boats. This is n't the Thames, but there's reason to believe the Tiber can be made livable for flora and flauna,'' said <PERSON> Aurelio </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Misiti </PERSON>, a sanitary engineer and professor at <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sapienza </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> His department works closely with the city on <LOCATION> Tiber </LOCATION> projects. While dictator <PERSON> Benito </PERSON> <PERSON> Mussolini </PERSON> had declared the river contaminated and banned swimming and transport in 1924, <PERSON> Misiti </PERSON> noted, postwar governments did n't get around to prohibiting the dumping of sewage into it until 1976. `` In 1974, <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> started building the first purification plant,'' <PERSON> Misiti </PERSON> said in an interview. `` Now there are four plants, but they can only handle a bit less than half the discharge, and that's just talking about urban waste, not industry's, which is supposed to be handled by the factories themselves.'' The sewage treatment program was supposed to have been completed years ago. <PERSON> Misiti </PERSON> said it should be finished by 1992 and `` after that the Tiber should return to normal.'' Just outside the city, fisherman pull in edible catch from the river, which begins its 251-mile course in the <LOCATION> Etruscan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Apennines </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Paola </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruggeri </PERSON> of the World Wildlife Fund says the city for the most part does n't enforce regulations forcing factories to purify their wastes before spilling them into the Tiber. Since 1982, her group has rented from the city a stretch of riverbank and intends to keep it as a green oasis. Willows, poplars, even a fig tree, lean out to the water, making that stretch look more like <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Twain </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> than a river channeled through a noisy, traffic-plagued international city. `` Every week volunteers come to clean it and every week we find a mountain of garbage,'' Ms. <PERSON> Ruggeri </PERSON> said. Until about a century ago, the city spilled down to the river banks, leaving <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> vulnerable to devastating floods, roughly every couple of hundred years. After many suggestions, including those of <PERSON> Giuseppe </PERSON> <PERSON> Garibaldi </PERSON>, the unification hero, the government began walling off the <LOCATION> Tiber </LOCATION> and demolishing buildings at river-level. Now pedestrians and cars move along, at bridge-deck level, with the Tiber's murky green waters are out of sight below. Earlier this year, when the city planned its annual April 21 celebrations of the legendary founding of <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> by <PERSON> Romulus </PERSON> along the left bank of the <LOCATION> Tiber </LOCATION>, it hosted an exhibit about excavations done in the last 10 years, when the river became a distinct department within the city's Superintendency of Archaeology. Tourists walking along the river can see the excavation of a three-level storehouse for jars of oil, wine and fish sauce left dockside by barges at the ancient port near what is now <LOCATION> Testaccio </LOCATION>, a blue-collar workers' neighborhood. `` In the past, the city lived on its river. <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> was a kind of <LOCATION> Venice </LOCATION>, a <LOCATION> Copenhagen </LOCATION>, a <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> or a <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Claudio </PERSON> <PERSON> Mocchegiani </PERSON> <PERSON> Carpano </PERSON>, head of the city's underwater archaeology department. `` A thousand years from now, when they dig up artifacts from the 20th century, they'll find out that the Tiber just ran through <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> and served as a sewer,'' <PERSON> Carpano </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed AMs, Aug. 31</NOTE>
