<TEXT>
 EDITOR'S NOTE _ The baroque <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Paul </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cathedral </ORGANIZATION>, designed by Sir <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Wren </PERSON>, is a beloved national monument in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. It is also at the center of a heated debate over modern architecture, since developers have a plan to rebuild much of the neighborhood near the cathedral. Leading the opposition is Prince <PERSON> Charles </PERSON>, who has emerged as a highly outspoken critic of today's buildings.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Prince </PERSON> <PERSON> Charles </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s best-known critic of modern building, has put architects on the line in the one place they can not afford to blunder: opposite St. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON>'s Cathedral. The domed cathedral in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, burial place of the nation's heroes, survivor of the Nazi blitz, is now the focal point of a heated debate about how cities should preserve their heritage while coping with modern needs The debate is symptomatic of a dilemma confronting all historic cities. In the words of architecture professor <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Jencks </PERSON>, `` In most cities of the West there is a genteel blood bath going on among those who have different tastes.'' Nowhere is that battle more intense than at Paternoster Square facing the north side of <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Paul </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION>. Developer <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Clegg </PERSON>, who owns most of the 7-acre site, plans to tear down a clump of undistinguished 1960s office blocks and put up more offices and shops. But Prince <PERSON> Charles </PERSON>, who got married in <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Paul </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION>, hates <PERSON> Clegg </PERSON>'s plan Although he has no architectural background, he has made the subject one of his favorite hobbyhorses, and his opinions carry weight. The baroque cathedral designed by Sir <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Wren </PERSON> is a beloved national monument. So the developers consulted with the <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> England </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> and other interested bodies, and invited seven architects to compete for the development. They also invited the heir to the throne to see the plans. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> disliked them all, telling a banquet in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION><LOCATION> 's </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> <LOCATION> financial </LOCATION> <LOCATION> district </LOCATION> last December: `` I was deeply depressed that none of them had risen to the occasion.'' `` Surely here, if anywhere, was the time and place to sacrifice some profit, if need be, for generosity of vision, elegance and dignity, for buildings which would raise our spirits and our faith in commercial enterprise and prove that capitalism can have a human face,'' the prince said. He likened much of the rebuilding of British cities since World War II to a rape, and in his most controversial utterance, suggested that modern <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> architecture was more unsightly than the rubble left by the German bombers. <PERSON> Clegg </PERSON> conceded in an interview that `` there's been a lot of criticism'' of the <ORGANIZATION> Arup </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION> plan which his <ORGANIZATION> Mountleigh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> chose. But he added that tastes change, noting that the existing plaza and buildings, now despised, were much admired when they went up in the 1960s, It is the prince's view that architecture should put people first. `` Hurrah for the champion of ordinary people ... Prince <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> is acting as the conscience of the nation,'' wrote architecture critic <PERSON> Gavin </PERSON> <PERSON> Stamp </PERSON> in The Daily Telegraph. The concrete shopping centers, dull office blocks and high-rise public housing that typify many British cities were built hastily to replace war rubble and solve the postwar housing shortage. Now, many are so hated that they are being dynamited by city authorities. Today, many inner-city housing complexes consist of cottages and gardens that mesh well with <PERSON> Charles </PERSON>' small-is-beautiful philosophy In <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> last March, <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> told a conference of international architects that after 40 years of town-planning in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, `` the results have been pretty disastrous.'' <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> went public on architecture in 1984, and has developed his theme with mounting fervor, claiming to speak for ordinary people whose views are ignored by the professionals. Although self-appointed as an arbiter of taste, 39-year-old <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> is one of the most popular members of the royal fmily, and his views get results. A projected extension to the National Gallery art museum in <LOCATION> Trafalgar </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION> was shelved after he called it a `` monstrous carbuncle on the face of a well-loved friend.'' Then he dismissed a 20-story tower design of the late <PERSON> Mies </PERSON> <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> der </PERSON> <PERSON> Rohe </PERSON>, for a site near the Bank of <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, as a `` giant glass stump.'' It too was scrapped. This year his written complaint about apartment blocks planned near his <LOCATION> Kensington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Palace </LOCATION> residence led to their alteration. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> likes classical style buildings recalling 18th century Georgian architecture, itself inspired by ancient <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>. He prefers buildings on a human scale with ground-level shops and somewhere to sit down. Many architects are aggrieved at being attacked by a man who has no formal architectural training. A Paternoster plan which the prince favors _ <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Simpson </PERSON>'s arcaded shops and low-level main buildings with columned facades and sculpture _ has met a lukewarm response. Architect <PERSON> Maxwell </PERSON> <PERSON> Hutchinson </PERSON>, tapped as the next president of the <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Architects </ORGANIZATION>, accuses the prince of abusing his privileged position. Writing in The Independent newspaper, <PERSON> Hutchinson </PERSON> denounced the `` fogeyish obsession'' with classical styles and wondered why the work of contemporary British architects such as <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON>, who co-designed the futuristic pipes-and-glass <LOCATION> Pompidou </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Center </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, is more admired abroad than at home. But <PERSON> Jencks </PERSON>, writing in The Observer weekly, remarked that most people now preferred `` to live in traditional houses at a village level, and possibly in some other century.'' <PERSON> Jencks </PERSON> also told a <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> audience that <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> had played a crucial role in widening the debate. `` We are closer now than we have been for 70 years to welcoming different schools and philosophies of architecture,'' he said. <PERSON> Wren </PERSON> also had problems. His first two designs for a replacement of the medieval cathedral, destroyed in the Great Fire of 1666, were rejected. His cathedral, which attracts 3 million visitors a year, has become a tough act for any architect to follow. Asked if he was worried by all the publicity, <PERSON> Clegg </PERSON>, 51, said: `` I think anything worthwhile is going to involve a whole lot of argument and it will be worth it. Even without <PERSON> Prince </PERSON> <PERSON> Charles </PERSON>, lots of people would have taken a strong interest in this site.'' <PERSON> Clegg </PERSON> estimates his development will cost $ 700 million to $ 850 million. He says he will apply for planning permission in December, start building in 1990 and hopes to complete the job by 1993. The rival plans were displayed for four weeks in the crypt of <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Paul </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> and attracted 7,000 visitors, 700 of whom left written comments which the developers say will be considered in the final plan.
</TEXT>
