 `` A Tiger's Tale'' -LRB- Paramount Home Video; VHS @ Beta, $ 79.95; Rated R -RRB- In `` A Tiger's Tale,'' a 19-year-old high school student named <PERSON> Bubber </PERSON> -LRB- <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Howell </PERSON> -RRB- falls for his girlfriend's mother, a divorced nurse named Rose -LRB- Ann-Margret -RRB-. It's easy to see why, but why she returns his affection _ setting off an affair lacking any heat at all _ is only one of the things that does n't make sense in this comedy-romance. There's also no good reason why <PERSON> Rose </PERSON>'s bratty daughter -LRB- <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> <PERSON> Preston </PERSON> -RRB- is allowed to get away with just about anything, including sabotaging her mother's sex life by poking a hole in her diaphragm. Or why <PERSON> Bubber </PERSON>, who intends to become a veterinarian, drags around a full-grown tiger on a leash in small-town <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. And then, there's the dialogue. Rose to <PERSON> Bubber </PERSON>: `` Sometimes when your hair's messed up, you look like a partially open can.'' Or <PERSON> Bubber </PERSON> to Rose: `` I may be 19 but I'm your man and you love me, and I'm going to go sleep on the couch where a dejected man is supposed to.'' And it was n't even nighttime. <PERSON> Ann-Margret </PERSON> tries and almost rises above her role, and <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Durning </PERSON> as <PERSON> Bubber </PERSON>'s father is good as usual. But the 1987 movie, written and directed by <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON>, son to <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON> and brother to <PERSON> Michael </PERSON>, is just dumb. _ By <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> MacVean </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
