<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 `` Live at the Whisky a Go-Go'' -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Elektra </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ X The songs are short, the arrangements smart and the band rambunctious on `` Live at the Whisky a Go-Go.'' X squeezes 24 songs into the two-record set. Just about everything rocks, and just about everything clicks. Lead guitarist <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Gilkyson </PERSON> is the star of the show. Many of the songs, such as `` Another Perfect Day,'' are built around <PERSON> Gilkyson </PERSON>'s riffs. And his breaks combine finesse with wild abandon; they're two parts rockabilly and one part machine gun. Singers <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Doe </PERSON> and <PERSON> Exene </PERSON> <PERSON> Cervenka </PERSON> are in top form, too. Neither has a particularly appealing voice, but they blend together well and come up with some great harmonies, often when the band is playing at top speed. For the uninitiated, only the absence of a lyric sheet keeps `` Live at the Whisky a Go-Go'' from being a perfect introduction to X. It's impossible to understand what <PERSON> Cervenka </PERSON> and <PERSON> Doe </PERSON> are singing most of the time, but the general theme seems to be that life is not a beach. `` I wish it would snow in <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lauderdale </LOCATION>, or at least rain and hail,'' <PERSON> Cervenka </PERSON> sings on `` Skin-Deep Town.'' On `` The World's a Mess,'' she contends just that: `` Go to hell and see if you like it,'' she suggests. It's good to know there are still a few bands out there with a bad attitude. _ By <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Wine </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 `` No Friction'' -LRB- Gramavision -RRB- _ Fool Proof This well-intentioned set of `` back to the roots'' blues by a group of jazz players from varied backrounds reinforces two lessons: Good intentions alone rarely get you very far, and it's not easy to blend musical styles Fool Proof combines the talents of nine jazzmen brought together by <ORGANIZATION> Gramavision </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Records </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rose </PERSON>, who was dismayed that many new jazz musicians were neglecting their blues roots. The result, `` No Friction,'' though well-played throughout, just does n't measure up as a good blues record. Too often, the jazz chops sound like an intrusion on the blues arrangements. And several of the songs lack emotional punch _ a fatal flaw in blues territory. There are a few bright spots. There's a tough workout of the old <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Green </PERSON> hit `` Love and Happiness,'' the only cover on the album; `` Red Car,'' composed by cornetist <PERSON> Butch </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON>, is a good, jumping tune; and saxophonist <PERSON> Dwight </PERSON> <PERSON> Andrews </PERSON>' `` Title Nine Blues'' has a certain eerie charm, if you can be charmed by 7:19 of moody riffing under a recitation of lines such as, `` Red blues ... brown blues ... I do n't recall blues ...'' Ultimately `` No Friction'' fails to satisfy. One gets the feeling, though, that the musicians here will keep the spirit of the project alive as they resume their own diverse work. Which might say something good about good intentions after all. _ By <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Rice </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
