<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Music Makers: A Human Hit Factory</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Holly </PERSON> <PERSON> Knight </PERSON> believes in the power of a good song. `` If people like the artist but not the songs, they wo n't buy the record,'' said <PERSON> Knight </PERSON>, who has written the hits `` Never'' for Heart, `` Love Touch'' for <PERSON> Rod </PERSON> <PERSON> Stewart </PERSON> and `` Better Be Good to Me'' for <PERSON> Tina </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON>. `` If you go to concerts, you can see the reactions of people when they go into a song they like or know. They sing and dance and go nuts. As soon as they recognize the hit, they stand up.'' But after years of catapulting others to the limelight, <PERSON> Knight </PERSON> is seeking some recognition of her own. She has just released her debut album, `` <PERSON> Holly </PERSON> <PERSON> Knight </PERSON>,'' and is counting on the strength of her writing to attract a following. `` I liked the songs so much that when I handed the record over to the label, I really did n't mind what song they picked for the single,'' she said. Knight grew up in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> wanting to be a rock star more than a songwriter. She began playing music at age 4 and was performing live as a teen-ager. Her talent as a songwriter emerged while she was a member of the groups `` Spider'' and `` Device.'' `` My songs were starting to be the singles and get more attention. When I left the group -LRB- Device -RRB-, I thought I'd write a song here or there and give them to people,'' she said. Her first hit came in 1983 with `` Love Is a Battlefield,'' recorded by <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Benatar </PERSON>. Knight does a softer version of the song on her own album. `` I really like <PERSON> Patti </PERSON>'s version of it. It gives people a chance to see how you can take the same song and make it sound really different,'' she said. Knight is pleased with all the interpretations of her songs, pointing out that the demos were similar to the finished product. She singled out <PERSON> Tina </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> for `` You Better Be Good to Me.'' `` I think the vocal delivery really suited her; ` Better Be Good to Me' suited her. It suited her psychologically. I think she did such a great job delivering it because she really meant it,'' <PERSON> Knight </PERSON> said. Her singing style is reminiscent of <LOCATION> Dusty </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION>, best known for such pop-soul songs as `` Son of a Preacher Man'' and `` I Only Want to Be With You.'' <PERSON> Knight </PERSON> said she does n't try to sound like any of her favorite singers, but admires their approach. `` <PERSON> Daryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>. I was influenced by him. <PERSON> Aretha </PERSON> <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON>. A lot of my favorite singers are great but not technically brilliant.'' Knight co-produced her album with <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Lord-Alge </PERSON>, who has worked with <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Springsteen </PERSON>, <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Gabriel </PERSON>, <PERSON> Madonna </PERSON> and <PERSON> Stevie </PERSON> <PERSON> Nicks </PERSON>. `` He -LRB- Lord-Alge -RRB- was very encouraging,'' she said. `` I purely went on instinct with him. Everything he said was right along the lines of what I was thinking.'' The album has a lush pop sound and little over-dubbing was used. `` It's not 48 tracks,'' <PERSON> Knight </PERSON> said. `` I did try to get three singers singing at once but I could n't use any of it because it sounded too big. It sounds rich because there is n't a lot of stuff on there so it gives room for what's on there to breathe.'' Still, songwriting is what <PERSON> Knight </PERSON> is known for, and the songs on her album were worked on over a long period of time. `` I may take months and months to write a song. I might work on it and then leave it for a while and then go back to it.'' Knight's writing is influenced by the Motown and Stax sounds of the 1960s. `` I owned a Supremes record before I owned a Beatles record,'' she said. `` I'm doing some new songs now. On one part I wanted to put horns on. The horns sounded really out of tune. They had that <ORGANIZATION> Memphis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sound </ORGANIZATION>, lazy out-of-tune horns. I was responding to those songs.'' Anyone hoping to turn an unrecorded <PERSON> Knight </PERSON> song into a hit will be disappointed: She is not prolific. `` I'm not the kind of writer that writes 40 songs and a few become hits. Just about every song I write has become a hit,'' <PERSON> Knight </PERSON> said. `` I do n't put a lot out there. In general, people call me and want to know if I have a tune sitting around, and I really do n't.'' Knight wants to tour, but will probably wait until next year. She points out again how important it is for the audience to recognize the songs. `` I'd like to have a couple of Top 10's so people will know some of the music. It's going to be more exciting for them as well as me if people know the music. `` It's down to that again: When you recognize a tune you dance and get into it. It helps tide me over. People are very comfortable with familiarity.''
