<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nashville Sound: Music Is Their Healer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GALLATIN, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Loney </PERSON> <PERSON> Hutchins </PERSON> gets his guitar out of the case, sits at a table and begins singing a tune written by a lady who's lucky to be alive: `` I could kiss your lips all night. `` Hold you in my arms with all my might. `` It's you who taught me `` The taste of love.'' Across the table, <PERSON> Tammy </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchem </PERSON> softly sings along with the words she wrote. `` It's pretty good if I do say so myself,'' she said. The 27-year-old woman from <LOCATION> Gastonia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, spent 2 -LCB- months in a coma following a traffic accident in February 1987. While driving to get horse feed, she was struck by a drunken driver in <LOCATION> Bessemer </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION> For the past 10 months she has participated in music therapy under the direction of <PERSON> Hutchins </PERSON>, a singer-songwriter and former associate of <PERSON> Johnny </PERSON> <PERSON> Cash </PERSON>. She is among about 25 people who once suffered severe head injuries receiving individual and group music therapy from <PERSON> Hutchins </PERSON> at <LOCATION> Cedarbrook </LOCATION>, a private treatment facility 40 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Nashville </LOCATION>. `` These people could be vegetating without this facility,'' says <PERSON> Hutchins </PERSON>. Patients start by listening to music, then graduate to singing or composing. Some go on fieiew bear markets in a favorable light. `` Remember, the only time you want stock prices to be at their peak is the day you plan to sell. In the meantime, you should be glad that the stock market periodically places its merchandise on sale.''
