<HEAD>Transplant, Grafting Techniques Could Help Against Brain Ailments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Doctors are n't swapping brains, or even thinking seriously about it, but they've taken steps toward transplanting parts of brains, or tissue from the body or fetuses to cure the body's most important organ. The ethical thickets surrounding it also are being explored, mainly one big question: Where will the brains come from? At <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, doctors are trying to reverse Parkinson's disease by implanting tissue from adrenal glands into the victims' brains. Doctors at <ORGANIZATION> Vanderbilt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> use a similar approach to treating Huntington's disease. For now, most of the testing is centered on Parkinson's, which affects up to 1 million Americans and results from destruction of part of the brain called the nigral tissue, which makes a message-carrying chemical, dopamine. At least 11 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> medical centers have tried transplanting dopamine-producing tissue from somewhere else in the body to the brain in 70 people, said Dr. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> McL </PERSON>. Black of <LOCATION> Brigham </LOCATION> and Women's Hospital. About half are better to some degree, and 10 percent are convincingly improved. Dr. <PERSON> Abraham </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lieberman </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> NYU </ORGANIZATION> neurologist, said the most impressive of his 11 patients is a doctor who could n't walk or even stand before surgery. He is far from cured, but can walk unassisted, live alone and go outside. The surgery costs $ 30,000 to $ 100,000, and many elderly Parkinson's patients are too sick to stand the two major operations on the abdomen and head that are required. To improve the outcome, doctors are considering using adrenal glands from young kidney donors, or from fetuses. Some success using tissue from spontaneously aborted fetuses has been reported by Dr. <PERSON> Ignacio </PERSON> <PERSON> Madrazo </PERSON> and colleagues at <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Raza </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. Dr. <PERSON> Anders </PERSON> <PERSON> Bjorklund </PERSON> at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lund </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> has had success in rats with <PERSON> Parkinson </PERSON>'s, but notes that a human needs far more tissue. Some biotechnology companies also are looking for ways to mass produce the fetal tissue in cell cultures. Dr. <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Brigham </LOCATION> and Women's said he does n't see any ethical barriers to transplanting tissue from aborted fetuses. However, researchers at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> have been prohibited from using aborted fetal tissue in transplants until an advisory committee can rule on the issues. Some have worried that women might abort fetuses so the tissue can be used in relatives, or might even sell their fetuses. <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> said he believes such excesses can be avoided.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Wide Differences in Child Diabetes Risk Highlight Basic Mystery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Children in <LOCATION> Rochester </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>, are about twice as likely to get the most serious form of diabetes as those in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> but face only two-thirds the risk of Finnish children, according to new research. The risk of insulin-dependent diabetes unexplainably varies 17-fold across 14 nations studied, running generally higher in cooler climates. Scientists are studying such differences for clues to a far more basic question: Just what causes insulin-dependent diabetes? The disease occurs because the insulin-producing cells of the pancreas have been destroyed by a misguided attack by the body's immune system The 1 million Americans with it must inject themselves with insulin every day to stay alive. Genes clearly play a key role in triggering the immune system's attack, but most people with the susceptible genetic background do not develop diabetes, and the geographic variation in rates is evidence of an environmental role, said <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> LaPorte </PERSON>, an epidemiologist at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pittsburgh </ORGANIZATION> A new study, reported in the August issue of the journal diabetes, compared insulin-dependent diabetes rates in children under age 15 from 14 countries. Rates ranged from 1.7 cases per 100,000 `` person-years'' in <LOCATION> Hokkaido </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, to 29.5 cases per 100,000 person-years in <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION>. A person-year is like a man-hour; it represents the equivalent of following one person for one year. Within the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the rates also showed variation: 9.4 in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION>, 11.4 in <LOCATION> Jefferson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>, 13.4 in <LOCATION> Allegheny </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Penn. </LOCATION>, 15.1 in <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>, 17.8 in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> and 20.8 in <LOCATION> Rochester </LOCATION>.
