<HEAD>NASA Consortium Seeking Private Rocket Launcher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A consortium is looking for a company to build, launch and recover a rocket it hopes to launch next year for a six-minute space flight with a half-dozen commercial experiments. The Consortium for Materials Development in Space will oversee the launch of the rocket carrying experiments that require low gravity. One is a study of making polyurethane foam in space, a process that may someday be used to build structures in orbit or on the <LOCATION> moon </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> Wessling </PERSON>, associate director. The consortium, a cooperative venture by the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alabama </ORGANIZATION>, industry and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, designethat they just ca n't do anything. `` Hopefully we will be able to explain this on the neurological level, in terms of what the nerve cells themselves are doing. Then we can look at developing drugs for it.''
</TEXT>
