<HEAD>Dollar Higher In Trading, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar rose swiftly in European trading this morning, recovering last week's losses. Gold prices were lower in quiet trading. Foreign exchange dealers said there was no central bank intervention in early trading but they predicted another round of concerted intervention this week to curb the dollar's rise. Traders in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> said the market was n't being led by hard economic facts or news, but by statements from public officials and a gut feeling that the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration wants a strong dollar to help the presidential candidacy of <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. `` This is a market led by declarations. -LRB- <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Secretary of <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> William </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- <ORGANIZATION> Verity </ORGANIZATION> says one thing, the White House another, and the market reacts accordingly,'' said a senior dealer in <LOCATION> Milan </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Verity </ORGANIZATION>'s statement last week that a lower dollar is needed if the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> is to right its massive trade imbalance had triggered a fall in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency. One dealer at a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bank in <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> said the dollar's recovery and current strength raised the chances that the <ORGANIZATION> Deutsche </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s central bank, will raise its discount rate at a meeting on Thursday In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where trading ends before <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s business day begins, the dollar rose 0.48 yen to a closing 133.88 yen. Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it was quoted at 133.85 yen. Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Friday's rates, included: 1.9137 West German marks, up from 1.8925; 1.6092 Swiss francs, up from 1.5915; 6.4835 French francs, up from 6.4125; 2.1615 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1390; 1,416.25 Italian lire, up from 1,405.50; and 1.2277 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2271 In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the British pound fell to $ 1.6860 from $ 1.7025 bid late Friday. Gold opened in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid price of $ 432.25 a troy ounce, up from $ 432.00 bid late Friday. But at midmorning today, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a lower recommended price of $ 429.70 In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, the bid price was $ 428.50, down from $ 432.50 bid late Friday. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold fell $ 1.61 to close at $ 432.01 compared to Saturday's $ 433.62. Silver was quoted in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> today at a bid price of $ 6.63 a troy ounce, down from Friday's $ 6.68.
