</ORGANIZATION> official said. Such status means Japanese investors will be allowed the same tax and other benefits accorded to Chinese enterprises. <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> will pledge a third round of Japanese yen credits to begin in 1990 in an amount still to be decided, the official said. <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> sources have suggested that the ceiling for the loan package will be about 800 billion yen, or around $ 6 billion. The current ceiling on Japanese loans to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> is 470 billion yen, or some $ 3.5 billion. The loans are for hydroelectric power and other major development projects. Trade between the two countries has moved into <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s favor in the last three years. In 1985 <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s surplus with <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> was $ 5 billion, but after the first six months of this year <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> is in the black by $ 500 million in a bilateral trade worth $ 8.6 billion. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> is <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s fifth-largest trading partner while <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> is <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s no. 2 trading partner.
