<HEAD>Chrysler's Canadian Branch Won't Recall Cars</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Canadian government can not make <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> recall 120,000 cars that may violate pollution laws even though the company recalled 492,000 cars for a similar reason in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, officials said. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> cars built between 1986 and early 1987 with 2.2-litre and 2.5-litre engines were recalled in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in April 1987 because a flawed fuel injector caused some cars to emit black smoke, which violated <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> pollution laws. But Canadian authorities can not force a similar recall because, until September 1987, Canadian emission laws were far less stringent than those in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, according to <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s Canadian subsidiary, which has refused a request by <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Canada </ORGANIZATION> to recall the cars `` We met with <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> in July,'' says <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Gourley </PERSON> of the department's energy emissions branch. `` But they said there was no reason to recall the cars because they met Canadian standards at the time -LRB- the cars were sold -RRB-.'' A <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Canada </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said Friday the company ca n't afford to recall old cars to comply with new laws `` Where would you draw the line on something like that, 1902?'' the spokesman asked. Most Chrysler K-cars, including <ORGANIZATION> Plymouth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reliants </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Dodge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aries </ORGANIZATION>, were among the models recalled in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Canadian emission-control laws f