<HEAD>London Shares Close Down</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with closing figures</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Stock prices closed lower in the slowest trading day of the year, with investors concerned that British interest rates may be raised again. The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index closed 12 points, or 0.7 percent, lower at 1,832.3. Volume was a scant 231.5 million shares, the lowest recorded in 1988, and well down from 342.4 million shares on Friday. The market remained depressed throughout the trading session by fears of another increase in the British commercial banks' base lending rate, which was raised to 11 percent from 10.5 percent two weeks ago. The government has raised interest rates several times this year to choke off potentially inflationary growth in the British economy. `` We certainly would n't rule out another rise in the short term,'' said <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Gardiner </PERSON>, an economist at <ORGANIZATION> Warburg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>. But the government might wait for more economic data to be released, and assessed, before acting, he added. Investors are awaiting Thursday's release of British trade figures for July, dealers said. Market sentiment also was undermined by the low level of trading activity during the summer vacation season, dealers said.
