<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Higher; Gold Prices Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar finished mostly higher Monday in skittish domestic trading after rising sharply overseas in the face of concerted central-bank intervention. Gold prices were mixed. <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> quoted a late bid price for gold of $ 433.20 a troy ounce, up from $ 431.25 late Friday. The dollar gained over the weekend in the Far East and continued to move higher when trading shifted to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. Dealers said there was no fundamental reason for the dollar's strength except that the market simply is bullish toward the currency. `` The dollar is the flavor of the month, and people are going for it,'' said <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> <PERSON> Dipple </PERSON>, chief dealer at <ORGANIZATION> Banque </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Francaise </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exterieure </ORGANIZATION>. A host of European central banks joined the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> in selling dollars when the currency was trading at about 1.9150 West German marks, but dealers said the dollar slipped only temporarily and then resumed its rise. The dollar closed higher in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and managed to finish mostly higher in domestic dealings despite a heavy bout of profit-taking and late central-bank intervention. `` It was really wild on the downside,'' said <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Watson </PERSON>, vice president at <ORGANIZATION> Swiss </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, commenting on the tumble the dollar took when the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> intervened. Despite the intervention, the dollar `` is still well in demand,'' said <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSO