<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> said Monday the demands of a homeless assistance group to stop the sales of foreclosed single-family dwellings would bankrupt a <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> mortgage insurance fund. The fund, sustained by the collection of mortgage insurance premiums from homebuyers who use <ORGANIZATION> FHA </ORGANIZATION> mortgage insurance, has helped millions of first-time, low - and moderate-income homebuyers since its creation in the 1930s, <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> said `` If we suspended sales, the <ORGANIZATION> FHA </ORGANIZATION> fund would be out of operation by the end of 1990,'' said <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dorsey </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> general counsel. Earlier this month, <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> called off a national sales campaign, which the department hoped would unload 15,000 foreclosed single-family properties, and it canceled an auction of 158 foreclosed <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, D.C.-area homes last weekend. The action was taken because of the threat of a lawsuit by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Project </ORGANIZATION>, which claims <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> is violating a homeless-assistance law passed last year that requires government agencies to consider the needs of the homeless before selling foreclosed properties. <PERSON> Dorsey </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> does not consider the foreclosed, single-family dwellings it is selling to be surplus property. The department considers the homes to be inventory, he said. Add