<DATELINE>PIKEVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A group of miners Monday filed a $ 1 billion federal lawsuit against the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> and its leadership, claiming the union prevented it from recovering wages lost during a 3 -LCB- - year strike The lawsuit contended the union did not represent the miners properly and discriminated against them because they did not take part in selective picketing. Named in the suit filed in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> included <PERSON> Rich </PERSON> <PERSON> Trumka </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> UMW </ORGANIZATION> president; <PERSON> Cecil </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON>, vice president; and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Banovick </PERSON>, secretary-treasurer. Each was accused of conspiring to keep the 406 plaintiffs from collecting benefits to which they should have been entitled. <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON>, a spokesman for the so-called `` Forgotten 400,'' said the lawsuit stemmed from an agreement reached in May between the <ORGANIZATION> UMW </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> A.T. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Massey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and its subsidiaries to end selective strikes launched against two eastern <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> mines in 1984. The agreement, requiring payment of $ 4.47 million to the union, also settled a lawsuit challenging <PERSON> Massey </PERSON>'s decision to turn the mines into non-union operations. About 700 miners, including <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON>, worked at the two mines until February 1983 when all but a maintenance crew were laid off. The remaining miners workers lost their jobs Sept. 30, 1984, the day before the two mines were sold to <ORGANIZATION> Sidney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a subsidiary of <ORGANIZATION> Ora </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mae </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, an operation owned by <PERSON> Massey </PERSON>. After the agreement was announced, <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> said the $ 4.47 million for lost wages and benefits would be divided among about 250 miners, who had been on selective strikes, with each receiving about $ 18,000. <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON>, of <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jacket </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> W. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, said the lawsuit contends that the <ORGANIZATION> UMW </ORGANIZATION> breached its duty of fair representation by limiting the number of members who would receive payments <PERSON> Hammond </PERSON> and other plaintiffs also contend they have been excluded from union meetings, thus violating the organization's constitution The lawsuit asks for a jury trial, plus $ 500 million in compensatory and $ 500 million in punitive damages. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, union spokesman <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Corcoran </PERSON> said late Monday that the union's legal department had not yet seen the lawsuit. But <PERSON> Corcoran </PERSON> said, `` The union is very confident that that settlement will be upheld in any court.'' <PERSON> Trumka </PERSON> pushed for the union's use of selective strikes, and on Oct. 1, 1984 <PERSON> Massey </PERSON> became the first target after the company refused to sign the union's national coal wage contract. Signing would have given <PERSON> Massey </PERSON>'s laid-off employees companywide re-employment rights. The union finally called off the sometimes violent strike in December 1985 when <PERSON> Massey </PERSON> agreed to settlement of an unfair labor practice charge, but selective strikes against the two subsidiaries continued until May.
