<FIRST>r f BC-Venezuela-LatinDebt     08-22 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Venezuela-Latin Debt,0352</SECOND>
<HEAD>Venezuela President Blasts Foreign Creditor Banks at International
Meeting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Venezuelan President <PERSON> Jaime </PERSON> <PERSON> Lusinchi </PERSON> leveled harsh criticism at foreign commercial banks Monday, blasting them for what he called their `` speculative'' treatment of Latin American debtors. `` Either we are loyal to our peoples and we look after their well-being, or we yield with those who impose conditions on us and violate our rights, and who only feel egoism, opulence and insatiable avarice,'' <PERSON> Lusinchi </PERSON> told conference delegates from 23 Spanish and Portuguese-speaking nations of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. `` The speculative criteria that predominates in big financial centers is incompatible with the interest of all people on earth,'' <PERSON> Lusinchi </PERSON> said. The president spoke during the opening ceremony of the Sixth IberoAmerican Conference held to organize the planned 1992 celebrations of the 500th anniversary of the discovery of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Lusinchi </PERSON>'s remarks come as <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> is seeking about $ 2.5 billion in new loans from foreign financial institutions to help cover a balance of payments deficit. Commercial banks widely are expected to seek economic austerity measures as a condition for new lending to <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Lusinchi </PERSON> labeled as `` absurd'' <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s current economic situation, in which countries from <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> are struggling to pay foreign debts of over $ 400 billion. <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>, which has a $ 34 billion foreign debt, is the region's fourth-largest debtor `` This is a threat to our most elemental rights, against our democratic stability, and against our societies that want well-being and freedom,'' he said. <PERSON> Lusinchi </PERSON> earlier this month sent a financial mission to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> to seek new debt financing. Venezuelan officials claim commercial bank creditors have reneged on a promise included in a 1987 partial debt refinancing to provide <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> with new funds and help it regain access to international financial markets. But despite recent rumors that <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> might declare a unilateral debt payment moratorium, <PERSON> Lusinchi </PERSON> and other top administration officials have said any suspension of payments would occur only if the financial mission failed and only in concert with commercial banks.
</TEXT>
